ty9 = Korea Economic Party\n| last_election9 = ''New Party''\n| seats9 = \n| seat_change9 = \n| popular_vote9 = \n| percentage9 = \n| swing9 = \n| image10 = [[File:Ahn Cheol-Soo cropped (cropped).jpg|150x150px]]\n| color10 = ff7417\n| leader10 = [[Ahn Cheol-soo]]\n| leader_since10 = 23 February 2020\n| leaders_seat10 = ''(Not standing)''\n| party10 = People Party (South Korea)\n| last_election10 = ''New party''\n| seats10 = \n| seat_change10 = \n| popular_vote10 = \n| percentage10 = \n| swing10 = \n| image11 = \n| leader11 = [[Hong Moon-jong]]\n| leader_since11 = 25 February 2020\n| leaders_seat11 = [[Proportional representation|Proportional]]\n| party11 = Pro-Park New Party\n| last_election11 = ''New party''\n| seats11 = \n| seat_change11 = \n| popular_vote11 = \n| percentage11 = \n| swing11 = \n| image12 = \n| leader12 = [[Lee Keun-shik]]\n| leader_since12 = 8 March 2020\n| leaders_seat12 = ''(Not standing)''\n| party12 = Open Democrats\n| last_election12 = ''New party''\n| seats12 = \n| seat_change12 = \n| popular_vote12 = \n| percentage12 = \n| swing12 = \n| title = Speaker\n| before_election = [[Moon Hee-sang]]\n| before_party = Democratic Party of Korea\n| posttitle = \n| after_election = \n| after_party = \n| map = \n| note = \n}}\n{{Politics of South Korea}}\n\n'''South Korea's 21st legislative election''' will be held on 15 April 2020. All 300 members of the [[National Assembly (South Korea)|National Assembly]] will be elected with 253 from [[first-past-the-post]] [[_South Korean Legislature Constituencies|constituencies]] and 47 from [[party-list proportional representation|proportional party lists]]. The elections are the first to be held under the new electoral system voted in 2020 due to the electoral reforms proposed by incumbent president [[Moon Jae-in]].<ref>{{cite web|title=\uc9c0\ubc29\uc120\uac70 \ub4dd\uc2e4 \uacc4\uc0b0\u2026 \ubbfc\uc8fc\ub2f9-\ud55c\uad6d\ub2f9, \uc811\uc810\uc5c6\ub294 \u2018\uac1c\ud5cc\u2019 \ub300\uce58|url=http://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LSD&mid=sec&sid1=100&oid=020&aid=0003117583|website=The Dong-a Ilbo|publisher=Naver|accessdate=25 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral system==\n{{see also|Elections in South Korea}}\n300 members of the National Assembly were elected in the 2016 elections, of whom 253 (84%) were elected from [[_South Korean Legislature Constituencies|single-member constituencies]] on a first-past-the-post basis, and 47 (16%) from [[closed list|closed party lists]] through [[Party-list proportional representation|proportional representation]] by the [[largest remainder method|Hare quota largest remainder method]], in accordance with South Korea's Public Official Election Act.<ref>Article 189, subsection (3), Public Official Election Act, {{cite web|url=http://www.nec.go.kr/engvote_2013/05_resourcecenter/02_01.jsp|title=Legislation & Judicial Decision|publisher=Republic of Korea National Election Commission|accessdate=9 April 2016}}</ref> To win seats through proportional representation, parties needed to pass an [[election threshold]] of either 5 single-member districts or 3% of the total list vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nec.go.kr/engvote_2013/02_elections/01_04.jsp|title=Election Districts and Representation System|publisher=Republic of Korea National Election Commission|accessdate=12 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Restrictions on candidates===\nCandidates for the National Assembly were required to pay a fee of {{Currency|amount=15000000|type=KRW|first=yes}} (US$14,000 as of December 2017), and under the [[National Security Act (South Korea)|National Security Act]] the Constitutional Court may block the registration of \"left-wing\", \"pro\u2013North Korean\" parties, though this provision has not affected recent elections.<ref name=\"SGI\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sgi-network.org/2015/South_Korea/Quality_of_Democracy|title=South Korea|publisher=[[Sustainable Governance Indicators]]|accessdate=9 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Date and process===\nThe 2020 election for the National Assembly will be held on 15 April, in accordance with Article 34 of the Public Official Election Act, which specifies that Election Day for legislative elections is held on \"the first Wednesday from the 50th day before the expiration of the National Assembly members term of office\".<ref>Article 34, Public Official Election Act, {{cite web|url=http://www.nec.go.kr/engvote_2013/05_resourcecenter/02_01.jsp|title=Legislation & Judicial Decision|publisher=Republic of Korea National Election Commission|accessdate=9 April 2016}}</ref> Eligible voters are required to be registered and at least 18 years old on the day of the election,<ref name=\"SGI\" /> and need to show an approved form of identification at the [[polling place]]. Polls on Election Day will be open from 6 a.m. to 6 p.m. [[Korea Standard Time]] (21:00\u201309:00 UTC, 14\u201315 April).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nec.go.kr/engvote_2013/04_news/04_01_voting.jsp|title=National Assembly elections: April 13, 2016|publisher=Republic of Korea National Election Commission|accessdate=12 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nSince 2009, voters have been able to vote overseas.<ref name=\"SGI\" /> The electorates can also cast early votes at polling stations in Korea without prior notice.<ref>{{cite news|last=Lee|first=Rachel|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2016/04/116_202228.html|title=Early voting begins for general election|newspaper=[[The Korea Times]]|date=8 April 2016|accessdate=9 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Fast-track controversy and Assembly violence ===\n\nThe legislative process of changing the election law, ongoing since February 2019, based on the 85th Article of the National Assembly law so called 'Fasttrack' was considered controversial by the main opposition Liberty Korea Party party and also by Bareunmirae Party member Yoo Seong-min, due to the absence of agreement between all parties.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hankyung.com/politics/article/2019042823491|title=\uc720\uc2b9\ubbfc \"\uc5ec\uc57c \ud569\uc758 \uc5c6\ub294 \uc120\uac70\ubc95 \uac1c\uc815\uc740 \ub2e4\uc218\uc758 \ud6a1\ud3ec\"|date=29 April 2019|website=hankyung.com|language=ko|access-date=1 January 2020}}</ref> [[Sohn Hak-kyu]], the leader of the Bareunmirae, and his decision to dismiss his fellow standing committee member [[Oh Shin-hwan]], to pass the \"Fasttrack\" has stirred up legal controversy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hankyung.com/politics/article/201904249582Y|title=\uc624\uc2e0\ud658 \uc0ac\ubcf4\uc784 \uac00\ub2a5? \ubd88\uac00\ub2a5?\u2026'\uad6d\ud68c\ubc95 48\uc870' \uc5ec\uc57c \uc0c1\ubc18\ub41c \ud574\uc11d|date=24 April 2019|website=hankyung.com|language=ko|access-date=1 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hankookilbo.com/News/Read/201904241823354816|title=\uc624\uc2e0\ud658 \uc0ac\ubcf4\uc784 \uac00\ub2a5\ud560\uae4c\u2026 \uad6d\ud68c\ubc95 48\uc870 \uc5c7\uac08\ub9b0 \ud574\uc11d|date=24 April 2019|website=\ud55c\uad6d\uc77c\ubcf4|language=ko|access-date=1 January 2020}}</ref> The Prosecution Service, however, declared Sohn's legal actions were not applicable to criminal charges.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://m.mt.co.kr/renew/view.html?no=2020010213173048488&type=outlink&ref=https://www.google.com|title=\uac80\ucc30 '\ud328\uc2a4\ud2b8\ud2b8\ub799 \ub3d9\ubb3c\uad6d\ud68c' \ud669\uad50\uc548\u00b7\ub098\uacbd\uc6d0 \ubd88\uad6c\uc18d \uae30\uc18c(\uc0c1\ubcf4)|last=MoneyToday|date=2 January 2020|website=m.mt.co.kr|language=ko|access-date=2 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nPhysical disruption of the National Assembly Secretariat made by [[Liberty Korea Party]] on April 2019, in order to interrupt the legal maneuver has been a subject of investigation, as violence in the National Assembly, and violation of the National Assembly law by the Prosecution Service.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yna.co.kr/view/AKR20190426149700001|title=\ud328\uc2a4\ud2b8\ud2b8\ub799 \uadf9\ud55c\ucda9\ub3cc, '\uc721\ud0c4\uc804' \uc774\uc5b4 '\uace0\uc18c\uace0\ubc1c\uc804'\uc73c\ub85c \ube44\ud654|last=\ubc29\ud604\ub355|date=26 April 2019|website=\uc5f0\ud569\ub274\uc2a4|language=ko|access-date=1 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Kim |first1=Bo-gyung |title=[KH Explains] What is behind political impasse, violence at National Assembly? |url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20190429000715 |work=The Korean Herald |accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.donga.com/news/article/all/20190909/97348169/1|title=\uac80\ucc30, \ud328\uc2a4\ud2b8\ud2b8\ub799 \uc9c1\uc811 \uc218\uc0ac\u2026\uc218\uc0ac\ub300\uc0c1 \uc758\uc6d0 109\uba85|date=9 September 2019|website=The Dong-a Ilbo|language=ko|access-date=1 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20190429000715|title=[KH Explains] What is behind political impasse, violence at National Assembly?|last=Herald|first=The Korea|date=29 April 2019|website=The Korea Herald|access-date=1 January 2020}}</ref> The Prosecution Service indicted several important members of the LKP, including leader [[Hwang Kyo-ahn]] and floor leader [[Na Kyung-won]] at the time, for criminal charges, mainly violence and violation of order.<ref name=\":0\" /> The indictment also included [[Democratic Party of Korea]] members.\n\n=== Electoral reform ===\n[[File:Electoral System composition of South Korea's National Assembly.svg|thumb|Red: 253, First-Past-the-Post<br />\nBlue: 30, Party-list proportional (compensatory)<br />\nGreen: 17, Party-list proportional (parallel)]]\nAn election reform bill, including a hybrid of the [[mixed-member proportional]] and [[Mixed Member Majoritarian|mixed member majoritarian]] (also known as Additional Member System and Parallel Vote respectively) systems, was passed on 27 December, despite physical obstruction by [[Liberty Korea Party]]. The eventual number of directly elected seats and proportional representation (PR) slots will be kept at 253 and 47, respectively, in the 300-member National Assembly. However, the majority of PR seats will be switched from a parallel system to a compensatory one.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20191227000589|title=National Assembly passes electoral reform bill|last=Herald|first=The Korea|date=27 December 2019|website=The Korea Herald|access-date=27 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nNot all PR seats will be distributed in a compensatory manner, however, with 17 of the 47 PR seats being distributed under the old [[parallel voting]] system, without reference to seats won at the constituency level, and the remaining 30 seats being distributed in the new compensatory system.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20191223004552315|title=(2nd LD) Opposition party launches filibuster against electoral reform bill|last=\uae40\uad11\ud0dc|date=23 December 2019|agency=Yonhap News Agency|access-date=3 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Reaction of the opposition ===\nThe main opposition [[Liberty Korea Party]] opposed the move and declared its plan to set up a satellite party to deal with the new election system changes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20191224005700315|title=Main opposition to set up satellite party for more proportional representation seats|last=\uae40\uc218\uc5f0|date=24 December 2019|agency=Yonhap News Agency|access-date=27 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Parties and candidates==\n{{see also|List of political parties in South Korea}}\n \nBoth major parties split to take advantage of the new partial [[mixed-member proportional]] electoral system put in place since the prior elections, with the main party only running in the constituencies (all their seats being therefore counted as [[overhang seats]]), and the satellite party only running for the proportional bloc seats (all seats therefore being filled with party lists).<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date= 2 March 2020|title= \ucc3d\ub2f9\uc120\uc5b8\ubb38|url= http://platformparty.kr/?page_id=23|work= |location= |access-date= 17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe parties are sorted by their current number of seats (prior to the election).\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! colspan=2 | Parties\n! Incumbent seats\n! Positioning and ideologies\n! Leader\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:{{Democratic Party of Korea/meta/color}}\" | \n| [[Democratic Party of Korea]]<br><small>[[Together Citizens' Party]]</small>\n| 120<br><small>8</small>\n| '''[[Centrism|Centre]] to [[Centre-left politics|centre-left]]'''<br>[[Liberalism]], [[Social Liberalism|Social liberalism]]\n| [[Lee Hae-chan]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:{{United Future Party/meta/color}}\" | \n| [[United Future Party]]<br><small>[[Future Korea Party]]</small>\n| 92<br><small>20</small>\n| '''[[Right-wing politics|Right-wing]]'''<br>[[National conservatism]], [[Economic liberalism]], [[Anti-communism]]\n| [[Hwang Kyo-ahn]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:{{Party for People's Livelihoods/meta/color}}\" | \n| [[Party for People's Livelihoods]]\n| 20\n| '''[[Centrism|Centre]]'''<br>[[Reformism]], [[Liberalism]], [[Social conservatism]]\n| [[Kim Jung-hwa (politician)|Kim Jung-hwa]]<br>[[Yu Sung-yup]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:{{Justice Party (South Korea)/meta/color}}\" | \n| [[Justice Party (South Korea)|Justice Party]]\n| 6\n| '''[[Centre-left politics|Centre-left]]'''<br>[[Social democracy]], [[Progressivism]]\n| [[Sim Sang-jung]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:{{Our Republican Party/meta/color}}\" | \n| [[Our Republican Party (2020)|Our Republican Party]]\n| 2\n| '''[[Far-right politics|Far-right]] <small>([[New Right (South Korea)|New Right]])</small>'''<br>[[Right-wing populism]], [[Social conservatism]], [[Ilminism]], Pro-[[Park Geun-hye|Park]]\n| [[Cho Won-jin]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:{{Minjung Party/meta/color}}\" | \n| [[Minjung Party]]\n| 1\n| '''[[Left-wing politics|Left-wing]]'''<br>[[Progressivism]]\n| Collective leadership\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:#FFA807\" | \n| [[Korea Economic Party]]\n| 1\n| '''[[Centre-right politics|Centre-right]]'''<br>[[Conservatism|Liberal conservatism]]\n| [[Choi Jong-ho]]<br>[[Lee Eun-jae]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:{{People Party (South Korea)/meta/color}}\" | \n| [[People Party (South Korea)|People Party]]\n| 1\n| '''[[Centrism|Centre]] to [[Centre-right politics|centre-right]]'''<br>[[Liberalism]], [[Reformism]]\n| [[Ahn Cheol-soo]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:{{Pro-Park New Party/meta/color}}\" | \n| [[Pro-Park New Party]]\n| 1\n| '''[[Right-wing]] to [[Far-right politics|far-right]]'''<br>[[National conservatism]], [[Right-wing populism]], [[Anti-communism]], Pro-[[Park Geun-hye|Park]]\n| [[Hong Moon-jong]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:{{Open Democrats/meta/color}}\" | \n| [[Open Democrats]]\n| 1\n| '''[[Centrism|Centre]] to [[Centre-left politics|centre-left]]'''<br>[[Liberalism]], [[Social liberalism]]\n| [[Lee Keun-shik]]\n|-\n|}\n\nParties not represented in the current National Assembly but plan on running candidates include:\n\n* The [[Green Party Korea]] (\ub179\uc0c9\ub2f9), a [[green politics|green]] political party.\n* The [[Labor Party (South Korea)|Labor Party]] (\ub178\ub3d9\ub2f9), a left-wing political party.\n* The [[:ko:\uc5ec\uc131\uc758\ub2f9|Women's Party]], a [[Radical feminism|feminist]] political party.\n* The [[:ko:\uae30\ubcf8\uc18c\ub4dd\ub2f9|Basic Income Party]], a single-issue party split from the [[Labor Party (South Korea)|Labor Party]] (\ub178\ub3d9\ub2f9) to campaign for [[universal basic income]].\n* [[Our Future|Future Party]], a youth-led centre-left to left-wing political party founded in 2017, focusing more on youth voting, outreach, and campaigning.\n* [[National Revolutionary Dividends Party]], a [[Syncretic politics|third position]] populist and anti-corruption political party.\n\n==Opinion polls==\n{{Main|Opinion polling for the 2020 South Korean legislative election}}\n\n== Results ==\n<!-- Parties are arranged by total number of seats, and, in case of a tie, by number of PR votes. The 