l", "comment": "(changed the color of dawn of liberty to black)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_South_Korean_legislative_election"}
{"title_page": "New Beacon School", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox school\n| name                  = The New Beacon Preparatory School\n| image                 = The New Beacon Shield.jpg\n| caption               = \n| image_size            = \n| coordinates           = {{coord|51.2001|0.2765|type:edu_region:GB_dim:100|format=dec|display=inline,title}}\n| motto                 = Dare Ex Fumo Lucem <br/>(Give light out of darkness)\n| established           = 1863\n| closed                = \n| type                  = [[Independent school (UK)|Preparatory School]]\n| religious_affiliation = \n| president             = \n| head_label            = Headmaster\n| head                  = Mike Piercy\n| r_head_label          = \n| r_head                = \n| chair_label           = \n| chair                 = \n| founder               = John Norman\n| specialist            = \n| address               = Brittains Lane\n| city                  = Sevenoaks\n| county                = Kent\n| country               = England\n| postcode              = TN13 2PB\n| local_authority       = \n| ofsted                = \n| staff                 = \n| enrolment             = c. 360\n| gender                = Boys\n| lower_age             = 4\n| upper_age             = 13\n| publication           = \n| free_label_1          = \n| free_1                = \n| free_label_2          = \n| free_2                = \n| free_label_3          = \n| free_3                = \n| colours               = Red and navy\n{{color box|Red}} {{color box|Navy}}\n| website               = {{url|www.newbeacon.org.uk}}\n}}\n\nThe '''New Beacon Preparatory School''' is an independent all-boys [[Preparatory school (UK)|preparatory school]], located at [[Sevenoaks]] in the [[English county]] of [[Kent]]. It admits both day students and [[boarding school|boarders]] aged between 4 and 13. The school also now offers a co-educational nursery for children 3 years of age and over. The school was founded in 1863, and has been on the current site since 1900. It had 62 students in 1913, and had grown to 400 students by 2008.<ref name=\"history\">{{cite web|url=http://www.newbeacon.org.uk/School-History |title=School History |publisher=New Beacon School |accessdate=2015-08-31}} (The school's History webpage suggests Constantine was headmaster from 1976 and served 32 years, so when \"numbers grew to reach four hundred with excellence at Common Entrance and Scholarship examinations being maintained\" that would be 2008.)</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn spring 1882, J. S. Norman took over '''The Beacon''', which had been established as a Preparatory school in 1863 at 18 St John's Road. As the numbers in the school grew, larger premises were needed leading to the decision in October 1897 to build a new boarding school in Sevenoaks. Land was acquired from [[William Amherst, 3rd Earl Amherst|Lord Amherst]]'s [[Montreal Park]] estate at Cross Keys, and construction of '''The New Beacon''' began in February 1899. The new building was ready by the end of the Autumn Term 1899.<ref>{{cite book |title=The New Beacon |first=Hugh |last=Barty-King |date=2000 |location=Great Britain |publisher=The Bath Press |isbn=0356219518}}</ref>\n\nIn January 1900 the New Beacon opened for the (continued) education of boys in a building with a capacity for 60 boarders. The exterior of the building changed little over the century, but the addition of a chapel in 1912 meant that the children no longer had to walk to [[Kippington]]. By 1913 the school had grown to 62 pupils and the fees were \u00a3120 per year for boarding and tuition, plus \u00a31 11s 6d for medical attendance. Other facilities included swimming baths, a miniature rifle range, a playground and two sports fields. During the First World War, staffing was depleted and the school's grounds and gardens had to be tended by staff and pupils. Thirty-seven former pupils were killed during the war, and another 75 Beaconians fell in the Second World War. Their names are noted on a memorial in the chapel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newbeacon.org.uk/about-us/history/|title=History|website=New Beacon School|access-date=27 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Post-war changes and the increase in day boys===\nAfter the war numbers continued to grow and the roll call was over 120 pupils in 1948. Over the next few decades, the school tripled in size. The appointment of Rowland Constantine in 1976 saw the end of a long run of headmasters from the Norman family; Constantine was in post for 32 years.<ref>{{cite book |title=The New Beacon |first=Hugh |last=Barty-King |date=2000 |location=Great Britain |publisher=The Bath Press |isbn=0356219518 |author-link= }}\n</ref>\n\nThe New Beacon is now predominantly a day school. In 2008 Mike Piercy was appointed as Headmaster and is the current incumbent.{{fact|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Notable former pupils==\nWriters\n*[[Siegfried Sassoon]], First World War poet<ref>[http://www.courier.co.uk/Kent-8217-s-greatest-WW1-poet-goes-online/story-22069162-detail/story.html \"First World War journals of Tunbridge Wells poet Siegfried Sassoon go online\", ''Kent & Sussex Courier'', 4 August 2014]. Accessed 16 Feb 2015</ref>\n*[[Anthony Powell]], novelist\n*[[Henry Green]],<ref>{{cite book |title=Prep School Children: A Class Apart |first=Vyvyen |last=Brendon |date=2009 |location=Great Britain |publisher=Bloomsbury |isbn=1847062873 |author-link= }}</ref> Novelist\nMilitary\n*[[Air Vice Marshall]] [[Cresswell Clementi]], CB, CBE.\n*[[Brigadier]] [[Archer Clive]], was a British Army officer who served during World War II.\n*[[Vice Admiral]] [[Timothy Laurence|Sir Timothy Laurence]], second husband of [[Anne, Princess Royal]]\nPolitics\n*[[Sherard Cowper-Coles|Sir Sherard Cowper-Coles]], diplomat\n*[[Charles Thomas Mills]], Conservative politician and [[Baby of the House]], killed in action in First World War\n*[[Arthur Mills, 3rd Baron Hillingdon]], Conservative politician\n*[[Lord Mayhew of Twysden]], former political advisor for Northern Ireland\nSport\n*[[Douglas Carr]], Cricketer, named one of Wisden's five Cricketers of the year in 1910. One England Cap.\n*[[Eliot Druce]], Cricketer\n*[[Sam Billings]], Kent and England cricketer\n*[[Joseph Choong]], tri-athlete\n*[[Ben Earl]], Saracens and England rugby player\n*[[Zak Crawley]], Kent and England cricketer\nOther\n*[[Charles Ede]], founder of the [[Folio Society]]\n*[[Henry Thynne, 6th Marquess of Bath]], landowner, creator of [[Longleat]] safari park\n*John Alexander Thynne, Viscount Weymouth, eldest son of 5th Marquess of Bath, killed near Vermelles on the 16th February 1916.<ref>[http://www.wiltshireatwar.org.uk/story/longleats-fallen-heir-john-alexander-thynne/ \"Longleat's Fallen heir\"]</ref>\n\n==Headmasters== \n*John Stewart Norman 1882\u20131929\n*Frank and Cecil Norman: Joint Headmasters 1929\u20131945\n*Cecil Norman 1945\u20131964\n*Denis Pratten 1964\n*John Norman 1964\u20131976\n*Rowland Constantine 1976\u20132008\n*Michael Piercy 2008\u2013present<ref>The New Beacon {{ISBN|0356219518}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nIn 2014, the Charity Commission for England and Wales urged New Beacon School to apologise to a former pupil in respect of statements made by the school to the Press.<ref name=\"urges-ver1\">{{cite news |title=Charity body urges The New Beacon School to reconsider apology over \"predatory paedophile\" |publisher=[[Sevenoaks Chronicle]] |date=24 October 2014|author=Doug Kempster }}</ref> The statements related to allegations made by the boy against Paul Woodward, a former music teacher, for abusing him at the school between 2005 and 2006.<ref name=\"jailed-ver1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/law-and-order/3447897/Music-teacher-at-prep-school-jailed-for-sexual-abuse-of-boys.html |title=Music teacher at prep school jailed for sexual abuse of boys |date=12 Nov 2008 |publisher=[[The Telegraph (UK)|The Telegraph]] |accessdate=5 May 2015}}</ref> In 2013, the Criminal Injuries Compensation Authority (CICA) made an award to the boy in compensation for the abuse the CICA found he had suffered. The ''Sevenoaks Chronicle'' reported that Woodward, who was convicted of sexual misconduct offences against other children and sent to prison indefinitely had been suspended from his post at the school during a previous police investigation involving allegations of sexual abuse but had been allowed back to work by a previous headmaster.<ref name=\"suspended-ver1\">{{cite news |title=Teacher was suspended then allowed back to work |publisher=[[Kent and Sussex Courier]] |date= November 13, 2008}}</ref> The school apologised to the child in 2015, and applauded him for his bravery in bringing Woodward to justice. The victim said that the apology came \"too late\".<ref name=\"toolate-ver1\">{{cite news |title=Sevenoaks school apology for sexual abuse 'too late' for teacher's victim |publisher=[[Sevenoaks Chronicle]] |date=April 30, 2015 |author=Doug Kempster}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.newbeacon.org.uk/}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:New Beacon Preparatory School}}\n[[Category:Schools in Sevenoaks]]\n[[Category:Preparatory schools in Kent]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox school\n| name                  = The New Beacon Preparatory School\n| image                 = The New Beacon Shield.jpg\n| caption               = \n| image_size            = \n| coordinates           = {{coord|51.2001|0.2765|type:edu_region:GB_dim:100|format=dec|display=inline,title}}\n| motto                 = Dare Ex Fumo Lucem <br/>(Give light out of darkness)\n| established           = 1863\n| closed                = \n| type                  = [[Independent school (UK)|Preparatory School]]\n| religious_affiliation = \n| president             = \n| head_label            = Headmaster\n| head                  = Mike Piercy\n| r_head_label          = \n| r_head                = \n| chair_label           = \n| chair                 = \n| founder               = John Norman\n| specialist            = \n| address               = Brittains Lane\n| city                  = Sevenoaks\n| county                = Kent\n| country               = England\n| postcode              = TN13 2PB\n| local_authority       = \n| ofsted                = \n| staff                 = \n| enrolment             = c. 360\n| gender                = Boys\n| lower_age             = 4\n| upper_age             = 13\n| publication           = \n| free_label_1          = \n| free_1                = \n| free_label_2          = \n| free_2                = \n| free_label_3          = \n| free_3                = \n| colours               = Red and navy\n{{color box|Red}} {{color box|Navy}}\n| website               = {{url|www.newbeacon.org.uk}}\n}}\n\nThe '''New Beacon Preparatory School''' is an independent all-boys [[Preparatory school (UK)|preparatory school]], located at [[Sevenoaks]] in the [[English county]] of [[Kent]]. It admits both day students and [[boarding school|boarders]] aged between 4 and 13. The school also now offers a co-educational nursery for children 3 years of age and over. The school was founded in 1863, and has been on the current site since 1900. It had 62 students in 1913, and had grown to 400 students by 2008.<ref name=\"history\">{{cite web|url=http://www.newbeacon.org.uk/School-History |title=School History |publisher=New Beacon School |accessdate=2015-08-31}} (The school's History webpage suggests Constantine was headmaster from 1976 and served 32 years, so when \"numbers grew to reach four hundred with excellence at Common Entrance and Scholarship examinations being maintained\" that would be 2008.)</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn spring 1882, J. S. Norman took over '''The Beacon''', which had been established as a Preparatory school in 1863 at 18 St John's Road. As the numbers in the school grew, larger premises were needed leading to the decision in October 1897 to build a new boarding school in Sevenoaks. Land was acquired from [[William Amherst, 3rd Earl Amherst|Lord Amherst]]'s [[Montreal Park]] estate at Cross Keys, and construction of '''The New Beacon''' began in February 1899. The new building was ready by the end of the Autumn Term 1899.<ref>{{cite book |title=The New Beacon |first=Hugh |last=Barty-King |date=2000 |location=Great Britain |publisher=The Bath Press |isbn=0356219518}}</ref>\n\nIn January 1900 the New Beacon opened for the (continued) education of boys in a building with a capacity for 60 boarders. The exterior of the building changed little over the century, but the addition of a chapel in 1912 meant that the children no longer had to walk to [[Kippington]]. By 1913 the school had grown to 62 pupils and the fees were \u00a3120 per year for boarding and tuition, plus \u00a31 11s 6d for medical attendance. Other facilities included swimming baths, a miniature rifle range, a playground and two sports fields. During the First World War, staffing was depleted and the school's grounds and gardens had to be tended by staff and pupils. Thirty-seven former pupils were killed during the war, and another 75 Beaconians fell in the Second World War. Their names are noted on a memorial in the chapel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newbeacon.org.uk/about-us/history/|title=History|website=New Beacon School|access-date=27 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Post-war changes and the increase in day boys===\nAfter the war numbers continued to grow and the roll call was over 120 pupils in 1948. Over the next few decades, the school tripled in size. The appointment of Rowland Constantine in 1976 saw the end of a long run of headmasters from the Norman family; Constantine was in post for 32 years.<ref>{{cite book |title=The New Beacon |first=Hugh |last=Barty-King |date=2000 |location=Great Britain |publisher=The Bath Press |isbn=0356219518 |author-link= }}\n</ref>\n\nThe New Beacon is now predominantly a day school. In 2008 Mike Piercy was appointed as Headmaster and is the current incumbent.{{fact|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Notable former pupils==\nWriters\n*[[Siegfried Sassoon]], First World War poet<ref>[http://www.courier.co.uk/Kent-8217-s-greatest-WW1-poet-goes-online/story-22069162-detail/story.html \"First World War journals of Tunbridge Wells poet Siegfried Sassoon go online\", ''Kent & Sussex Courier'', 4 August 2014]. Accessed 16 Feb 2015</ref>\n*[[Anthony Powell]], novelist\n*[[Henry Green]],<ref>{{cite book |title=Prep School Children: A Class Apart |first=Vyvyen |last=Brendon |date=2009 |location=Great Britain |publisher=Bloomsbury |isbn=1847062873 |author-link= }}</ref> Novelist\nMilitary\n*[[Air Vice Marshall]] [[Cresswell Clementi]], CB, CBE.\n*[[Brigadier]] [[Archer Clive]], was a British Army officer who served during World War II.\n*[[Vice Admiral]] [[Timothy Laurence|Sir Timothy Laurence]], second husband of [[Anne, Princess Royal]]\nPolitics\n*[[Sherard Cowper-Coles|Sir Sherard Cowper-Coles]], diplomat\n*[[Charles Thomas Mills]], Conservative politician and [[Baby of the House]], killed in action in First World War\n*[[Arthur Mills, 3rd Baron Hillingdon]], Conservative politician\n*[[Lord Mayhew of Twysden]], former political advisor for Northern Ireland\nSport\n*[[Eliot Druce]], Cricketer\n*[[Sam Billings]], Kent and England cricketer\n*[[Joseph Choong]], tri-athlete\n*[[Ben Earl]], Saracens and England rugby player\n*[[Zak Crawley]], Kent and England cricketer\nOther\n*[[Charles Ede]], founder of the [[Folio Society]]\n*[[Henry Thynne, 6th Marquess of Bath]], landowner, creator of [[Longleat]] safari park\n*John Alexander Thynne, Viscount Weymouth, eldest son of 5th Marquess of Bath, killed near Vermelles on the 16th February 1916.<ref>[http://www.wiltshireatwar.org.uk/story/longleats-fallen-heir-john-alexander-thynne/ \"Longleat's Fallen heir\"]</ref>\n\n==Headmasters== \n*John Stewart Norman 1882\u20131929\n*Frank and Cecil Norman: Joint Headmasters 1929\u20131945\n*Cecil Norman 1945\u20131964\n*Denis Pratten 1964\n*John Norman 1964\u20131976\n*Rowland Constantine 1976\u20132008\n*Michael Piercy 2008\u2013present<ref>The New Beacon {{ISBN|0356219518}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nIn 2014, the Charity Commission for England and Wales urged New Beacon School to apologise to a former pupil in respect of statements made by the school to the Press.<ref name=\"urges-ver1\">{{cite news |title=Charity body urges The New Beacon School to reconsider apology over \"predatory paedophile\" |publisher=[[Sevenoaks Chronicle]] |date=24 October 2014|author=Doug Kempster }}</ref> The statements related to allegations made by the boy against Paul Woodward, a former music teacher, for abusing him at the school between 2005 and 2006.<ref name=\"jailed-ver1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/law-and-order/3447897/Music-teacher-at-prep-school-jailed-for-sexual-abuse-of-boys.html |title=Music teacher at prep school jailed for sexual abuse of boys |date=12 Nov 2008 |publisher=[[The Telegraph (UK)|The Telegraph]] |accessdate=5 May 2015}}</ref> In 2013, the Criminal Injuries Compensation Authority (CICA) made an award to the boy in compensation for the abuse the CICA found he had suffered. The ''Sevenoaks Chronicle'' reported that Woodward, who was convicted of sexual misconduct offences against other children and sent to prison indefinitely had been suspended from his post at the school during a previous police investigation involving allegations of sexual abuse but had been allowed back to work by a previous headmaster.<ref name=\"suspended-ver1\">{{cite news |title=Teacher was suspended then allowed back to work |publisher=[[Kent and Sussex Courier]] |date= November 13, 2008}}</ref> The school apologised to the child in 2015, and applauded him for his bravery in bringing Woodward to justice. The victim said that the apology came \"too late\".<ref name=\"toolate-ver1\">{{cite news |title=Sevenoaks school apology for sexual abuse 'too late' for teacher's victim |publisher=[[Sevenoaks Chronicle]] |date=April 30, 2015 |author=Doug Kempster}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.newbeacon.org.uk/}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:New Beacon Preparatory School}}\n[[Category:Schools in Sevenoaks]]\n[[Category:Preparatory schools in Kent]]\n", "name_user": "Jimvinkiss", "label": "safe", "comment": "inserted Douglas Carr", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_Beacon_School"}
{"title_page": "Lemonade (Beyonc\u00e9 album)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Lemonade\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Beyonc\u00e9]]\n| cover      = Beyonce - Lemonade (Official Album Cover).png\n| border     = yes\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|2016|04|23}}\n| recorded   = June 2014 \u2013 July 2015\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n* The Beehive\n* [[Conway Recording Studios|Conway]]\n* [[Henson Recording Studios|Henson]]\n* [[Record Plant]] ([[Los Angeles]], California)\n* [[Larrabee Sound Studios]]\n* Mirrorball\n* [[Pacifique Recording Studios|Pacifique]] ([[North Hollywood]], California)\n* Apex\n* [[Mad Decent]] ([[Burbank, California]])\n* Skip Saylor ([[Northridge, California]])\n* [[Jungle City Studios|Jungle City]] ([[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]])\n| genre      = [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]<ref name=\"Wilson\">{{cite web|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/music_box/2016/04/beyonc_s_lemonade_is_incredible_as_a_visual_album_but_how_is_it_as_just.html|title=Beyonc\u00e9's \"Lemonade\" is incredible as a visual album. But how is it as just music?|work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]|last=Wilson|first=Carl|date=April 25, 2016|accessdate=October 2, 2016|quote=...contemporary R&B album}}</ref>\n| length     = {{duration|m=45|s=42}}\n| label      =\n* [[Parkwood Entertainment|Parkwood]]\n* [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n| director   =\n* [[Kahlil Joseph (filmmaker)|Kahlil Joseph]]\n* Beyonc\u00e9 Knowles [[Melina Matsoukas]]\n| producer   =\n* Beyonc\u00e9\n* Ben Billions\n* [[Boots (musician)|Boots]]\n* [[DannyBoyStyles]]\n* [[Diplo]]\n* [[Ezra Koenig]]\n* [[Jack White]]\n* [[James Blake (musician)|James Blake]]\n* Jeremy McDonald\n* [[Jonny Coffer]]\n* [[Just Blaze]]\n* [[Kevin Garrett (musician)|Kevin Garrett]]\n* [[MeLo-X]]\n* [[Mike Dean (record producer)|Mike Dean]]\n* [[Mike Will Made It]]\n* Vincent Berry II\n* [[Wynter Gordon]]\n| prev_title = [[Beyonc\u00e9: Platinum Edition]]/[[More Only]]\n| prev_year  = 2014\n| next_title = [[Everything Is Love]]\n| next_year  = 2018\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = Beyonc\u00e9 studio albums\n | type       = studio\n | prev_title = [[Beyonc\u00e9 (album)|Beyonc\u00e9]]\n | prev_year  = 2013\n | title      = Lemonade\n | year       = 2016\n | next_title = \n | next_year  = \n}}\n{{Singles\n | name        = Lemonade\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Formation (song)|Formation]]\n | single1date = February 6, 2016\n | single2     = [[Sorry (Beyonc\u00e9 song)|Sorry]]\n | single2date = May 3, 2016\n | single3     = [[Hold Up (song)|Hold Up]]\n | single3date = August 16, 2016\n | single4     = [[Freedom (Beyonc\u00e9 song)|Freedom]]\n | single4date = September 9, 2016\n | single5     = [[All Night (Beyonc\u00e9 song)|All Night]]\n | single5date = December 6, 2016\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Lemonade''''' is the sixth studio album by American singer [[Beyonc\u00e9]], released on April 23, 2016, by [[Parkwood Entertainment]] and [[Columbia Records]]. It was her second \"visual album\" following her [[Beyonc\u00e9 (album)|2013 eponymous fifth album]], is a [[concept album]] and a [[song cycle]]. Primarily an [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] album, ''Lemonade'' encompasses a variety of genres, including [[pop music|pop]], [[reggae]], [[blues]], [[rock music|rock]], [[hip hop music|hip hop]], [[soul music|soul]], [[funk]], [[Americana (music)|Americana]], [[country music|country]], [[gospel music|gospel]], [[electronic music|electronic]], and [[Trap music (hip hop)|trap]]. It features [[Guest vocals|guest vocal]]s from [[James Blake (musician)|James Blake]], [[Kendrick Lamar]], [[The Weeknd]], and [[Jack White]], and contains [[Sampling (music)|samples]] and interpolations of a number of hip hop and rock songs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/beyonces-lemonade-a-guide-to-the-samples-and-interpolations-20160426|title=Beyonc\u00e9's 'Lemonade': A Guide to Samples and Interpolations|work=Rolling Stone|date=April 26, 2016|accessdate=June 25, 2016|author=Drake, David}}</ref>\n\n''Lemonade'' was made available for [[Streaming media|streaming]] on April 23, 2016 through Beyonc\u00e9's co-owned streaming service [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]]. It was released for purchase the following day, and was briefly available on [[Apple Music]] before reverting back into an album exclusively for purchase on Tidal. It was then released for physical retailers on May 6. The album debuted at number one on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], selling 485,000 copies in its first week of sales (653,000 with additional [[album-equivalent units]]) and earning Beyonc\u00e9 her sixth consecutive number-one album on the chart. By the end of 2016, ''Lemonade'' had sold over 1.5 million copies in the United States, making it the third-bestselling album of the year in the US.<ref name=\"billboard\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7647018/drake-views-nielsen-music-top-album-2016-us|title=Drake's 'Views' Is Nielsen Music's Top Album of 2016 in the U.S.|date=January 5, 2017|work=Billboard|accessdate=June 17, 2019}}</ref> Globally, however, it was the best-selling album of 2016, according to the [[International Federation of the Phonographic Industry]] (IFPI), with 2.5 million copies shipped globally.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ifpi.org/downloads/GMR2017.pdf|title=Global Music Report 2017 (page 9)|work=[[IFPI]]|date=April 25, 2017|accessdate=April 25, 2017}}</ref> On April 23, 2019, exactly 3 years from its original release, the album was made available on all streaming platforms, with the [[Spotify]] release and Apple Music re-release making headlines.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/beyonces-number-1-album-lemonade-will-finally-get-a-wider-streaming-release-on-april-23__26110/|title=Beyonce's Number 1 album Lemonade will finally get a wider streaming release on April 23|work=[[Official Charts Company]]|date=April 18, 2019|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIt was supported by five [[Single (music)|single]]s: \"[[Formation (song)|Formation]]\", \"[[Sorry (Beyonc\u00e9 song)|Sorry]]\", \"[[Hold Up (song)|Hold Up]]\", \"[[Freedom (Beyonc\u00e9 song)|Freedom]]\" featuring Kendrick Lamar, and \"[[All Night (Beyonc\u00e9 song)|All Night]]\"; \"[[Daddy Lessons]]\" featuring the [[Dixie Chicks]]. The album appeared on several publications' year-end lists, with ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' listing it at number one.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/50-best-albums-of-2016-w451265/david-bowie-blackstar-w451267|title=50 Best Albums of 2016|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=November 28, 2016|accessdate=November 28, 2016}}</ref> In April 2016, Beyonc\u00e9 embarked on [[The Formation World Tour]] to promote the album, an [[Stadium|all-stadium]] tour visiting North America and Europe, the year's second highest-grossing tour.\n\n''Lemonade'' was nominated for nine awards at the [[59th Annual Grammy Awards]] in 2017, winning [[Grammy Awards]] for [[Grammy Award for Best Urban Contemporary Album|Best Urban Contemporary Album]] and [[Grammy Award for Best Music Video|Best Music Video]], \"Formation\" received nominations for [[Grammy Award for Record of the Year|Record of the Year]], [[Grammy Award for Song of the Year|Song of the Year]], and Best Music Video, while \"Hold Up\", \"Don't Hurt Yourself\", and \"Freedom\" were nominated in pop, rock, and rap categories, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/music/awards/lemonade-album-of-the-year-grammys-beyonce-25-blackstar-1201934214/|title=2017 Grammy Awards: Adele, Beyonc\u00e9 Lead Nominations|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Christopher|last=Morris|date=December 6, 2016|accessdate=December 6, 2016}}</ref> The album won a [[Peabody Award]] in the Entertainment category. The review aggregation site [[Metacritic]] lists it as the second-most critically acclaimed album of 2016 and the eighteenth-most critically acclaimed album of all time.<ref>{{cite web|title=Music Critic Top 10 Lists - Best of 2016|url=http://www.metacritic.com/feature/critics-pick-top-10-best-albums-of-2016?ref=hp|first=Jason|last=Dietz|date=28 November 2016|accessdate=27 July 2017|work=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref> In 2017, [[National Public Radio|NPR]] named ''Lemonade'' as the sixth greatest album made by a woman.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2017/07/20/538307314/turning-the-tables-150-greatest-albums-made-by-women-page-15|title=The 150 Greatest Albums Made By Women|work=[[National Public Radio]]|first=Anastasia|last= Tsioulcas|date=July 24, 2017|accessdate=September 4, 2017}}</ref> In June 2019, ''Lemonade'' was certified 3\u00d7 Platinum, having sold up to 3 million album-equivalent units in the United States alone.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/|title=Gold & Platinum|website=RIAA|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-04}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\n[[File:Beyonce and Bruno Mars Super Bowl 50.jpg|thumbnail|left|230px|Beyonc\u00e9 performing during the [[Super Bowl 50 halftime show]] as special guest for [[Coldplay]] on February 7, 2016]]\n\nOn February 6, 2016, Beyonc\u00e9 released \"[[Formation (song)|Formation]]\" free on the music streaming service [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]] and its accompanying [[music video]] on her official [[YouTube]] account.<ref>{{cite news|author=Bartleet, Larry|url=http://www.nme.com/news/beyonce/91295|title=Listen to Beyonc\u00e9's new surprise single 'Formation'|date=February 6, 2016|work=[[NME]]|accessdate=February 8, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160207064001/http://www.nme.com/news/beyonce/91295|archivedate=February 7, 2016}}</ref> The following day, Beyonc\u00e9 performed \"Formation\" during her performance at the [[Super Bowl 50 halftime show]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/feb/08/beyonce-black-panthers-homage-black-lives-matter-super-bowl-50|title=Beyonc\u00e9 unleashes Black Panthers homage at Super Bowl 50|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=February 8, 2016|accessdate=February 8, 2016}}</ref> Immediately after the performance, a commercial aired announcing [[The Formation World Tour]], which kicked off in [[Miami]], [[Florida]] on April 27, 2016, with the first pre-sales going on sale just two days after the announcement on February 9, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cosmopolitan.co.uk/entertainment/news/a41094/beyonce-announces-world-tour-super-bowl/|title=Beyonc\u00e9 announced a new world tour after her Super Bowl halftime performance|work=[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]|first=Ellen|last=Scott|date=February 8, 2016|accessdate=February 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\nLeading up to the tour announcement, Beyonc\u00e9 was both praised and criticized over her new song and [[Black Panther Party|Black Panther]]-influenced costume for the Super Bowl halftime performance. As a result of this, the [[hashtag]]s \"#BoycottBeyonce\" and \"#IStandWithBeyonce\" began trending on [[social media]] platforms such as [[Twitter]]. A group of protesters planned to stage an \"anti-Beyonc\u00e9\" rally outside of the [[National Football League|NFL]]'s headquarters in [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]] on the day general sale of tickets went for sale,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newyork.cbslocal.com/2016/02/09/beyonce-super-bowl-controversy/|title=Anger: Anti-Beyonc\u00e9 Rally Planned For Next Week At NFL Headquarters|work=CBS New York|date=February 9, 2016|accessdate=February 15, 2016}}</ref> but no protesters showed up and instead dozens of Beyonc\u00e9 supporters held a rally for her.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2016/02/16/entertainment/beyonce-rally-feat/index.html|title=Only fans in 'Formation' at planned anti-Beyonc\u00e9 rally|publisher=CNN|first=Lisa Respers|last=France|date=February 16, 2016|accessdate=February 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\nWhen asked what she wants to accomplish with the next phase of her career in an interview with [[Elle (magazine)|''Elle'']] published April 4, 2016, Beyonc\u00e9 said \"I hope I can create art that helps people heal. Art that makes people feel proud of their struggle. Everyone experiences pain, but sometimes you need to be uncomfortable to transform.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elle.com/fashion/a35286/beyonce-elle-cover-photos/|title=Beyonc\u00e9 Wants to Change the Conversation|last=Gottesman|first=Tamar|date=2016-04-04|website=ELLE|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n== Recording and production ==\n''Lemonade'' was recorded between June 2014 and July 2015 across 11 studios in the United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://happymag.tv/engineering-the-sound-beyonces-lemonade/|title=Engineering the Sound: Beyonc\u00e9's 'Lemonade'|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref> The album was written in stages, with Beyonc\u00e9 retreating to her home to work on the recordings with recording and mixing engineer Stuart White, as well as to take care of her daughter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.audiotechnology.com/features/mix-masters-making-lemonade-with-beyonces-right-hand-man-stuart-white|title=MIX MASTERS: MAKING LEMONADE WITH BEYONCE'S RIGHT-HAND MAN, STUART WHITE|last=says|first=Michael|date=2016-09-22|website=AudioTechnology|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>\n\n[[Jay-Z]] recounted how he and Beyonc\u00e9 were in the studio to record music, both separately and together, describing it as \"using our art almost like a therapy session\" after his infidelity. The music that Beyonc\u00e9 recorded separately was what became ''Lemonade'' and was released first.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/article/42177522/jay-z-admits-to-cheating-on-beyonce-and-says-music-was-their-therapy|title=Jay-Z admits to cheating on Beyonce and says music was their 'therapy'|date=2017-11-30|website=BBC Newsbeat|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\nBeyonc\u00e9 had the idea to write each song corresponding to the eleven chapters that can be seen in the ''Lemonade'' film, and posted moodboards around the studio representing each chapter to provide direction to her collaborators.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.idolator.com/7688771/mnek-language-gay-black-representation-beyonce-interview|title=MNEK On 'Language,' Representation & Working With Beyonc\u00e9: Interview|date=2018-11-27|website=idolator|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/triplej/news/musicnews/mnek-on-three-of-his-biggest-hits/9700128|title=MNEK unpacks three of his biggest hits|last=Tencic|first=Nat|date=2018-04-26|website=triple j|language=en|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref> Beyonc\u00e9 and her collaborators also played music in the studio to inspire each other.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/65045-beyonces-lemonade-collaborator-melo-x-gives-first-interview-on-making-of-the-album/|title=Beyonc\u00e9's Lemonade Collaborator MeLo-X Gives First Interview on Making of the Album|website=Pitchfork|language=en|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>\n\n''Lemonade'' was produced through Beyonc\u00e9's synthesis of the work of many collaborators, including both popular and lesser known artists.<ref name=\":18\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/making-lemonade-inside-beyonces-collaborative-masterpiece-85854/|title=Making 'Lemonade': Inside Beyonce's New Masterpiece|last=Peisner|first=David|last2=Peisner|first2=David|date=2016-04-28|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref> [[MNEK]] relayed how \"[[Hold Up (song)|Hold Up]]\" was written, saying \"The way Beyonc\u00e9 works, the song is a jigsaw piece and then she will piece various elements. It could be a bit that she's written, a bit that someone else has written and she\u2019ll make that the [[Bridge (music)|bridge]]; a bit I've written she\u2019ll make the [[Thirty-two-bar form|middle eight]]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/triplej/news/musicnews/mnek-on-three-of-his-biggest-hits/9700128|title=MNEK unpacks three of his biggest hits|last=Tencic|first=Nat|date=2018-04-26|website=triple j|language=en|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref> MNEK also explains that Beyonc\u00e9 was \"overlooking everything, saying ''\"''I like this, I like that, this is how this should sound, this is how that should sound.''\"''\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/65132-beyonces-lemonade-collaborator-mnek-talks-lending-hold-up-a-key-line/|title=Beyonc\u00e9's Lemonade Collaborator MNEK Talks Lending \"Hold Up\" a Key Line|website=Pitchfork|language=en|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref> \"[[Don't Hurt Yourself (Beyonc\u00e9 song)|Don't Hurt Yourself]]\" collaborator [[Jack White]] describes how \"she took just sort of a sketch of a lyrical outline and turned into the most bodacious, vicious, incredible song... I'm so amazed at what she did with it.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2016/09/10/493177019/jack-white-on-detroit-beyonc-and-where-songs-come-from|title=Jack White On Detroit, Beyonc\u00e9 And Where Songs Come From|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref> \"Hold Up\" and \"[[Sorry (Beyonc\u00e9 song)|Sorry]]\" co-writer and co-producer [[MeLo-X]] explains that \"she has a way of creating that I\u2019ve never seen before as an artist. She produces, alters and arranges tracks in ways I wouldn\u2019t think of.\"<ref name=\":18\" /> When talking about how he scored the ''Lemonade'' film as well, MeLo-X explains \"She's hands on with everything. She gives direction on everything and is very involved with the whole process. It's inspiring to see an artist on that level be able to just still have an eye for certain things and an ear... We would just sit down and go over with different things and different scenes and sounds and kind of put it together piece by piece.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/65045-beyonces-lemonade-collaborator-melo-x-gives-first-interview-on-making-of-the-album/|title=Beyonc\u00e9's Lemonade Collaborator MeLo-X Gives First Interview on Making of the Album|website=Pitchfork|language=en|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>\n\n== Film ==\n[[File:Malcolm X NYWTS 4.jpg|thumb|upright=0.75|right|The film samples work by [[Malcolm X]].|alt=Malcolm X in 1964]]\n''Lemonade'' was accompanied by the release of a sixty-five-minute film of the same title, produced by [[Good Company (company)|Good Company]] and Jonathan Lia, which premiered on [[HBO]] on April 23, 2016,<ref name=\"pfk42416\">{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/63381-beyonce-releases-new-album-lemonade-featuring-kendrick-lamar-jack-white-the-weeknd-james-blake/|title=Beyonc\u00e9 Releases New Album Lemonade Featuring Kendrick Lamar, Jack White, the Weeknd, James Blake|date=April 23, 2016|accessdate=April 23, 2016|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]}}</ref> logging 787,000 viewers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/news/game-of-thrones-premiere-ratings-season-6-1201759863/|title='Game of Thrones' Premiere Draws 8 Million TV Viewers \u2014 Just Shy of Series High|work=Variety|date=April 26, 2016|accessdate=August 22, 2016}}</ref>  It is divided into eleven chapters, titled \"Intuition\", \"Denial\", \"Anger\", \"Apathy\", \"Emptiness\", \"Accountability\", \"Reformation\", \"Forgiveness\", \"Resurrection\", \"Hope\", and \"Redemption\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hall|first1=Gerrad|title=Lemonade: Best moments from Beyonc\u00e9's HBO event|url=http://www.ew.com/article/2016/04/23/beyonce-lemonade-hbo-best-moments|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=August 7, 2016|date=April 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe film uses poetry and prose written by expatriate Somali poet [[Warsan Shire]]; her poems which she adapted were \"The Unbearable Weight of Staying\", \"Dear Moon\", \"How to Wear Your Mother's Lipstick\", \"Nail Technician as Palm Reader\", and \"For Women Who Are Difficult to Love\".<ref name=\"Vogue Shire\">{{cite web|first=Patricia|last=Garcia|title=Warsan Shire Is the Next Beyonc\u00e9-Backed Literary Sensation|url=http://www.vogue.com/13429615/warsan-shire-lemonade-poet/|work=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]|accessdate=April 27, 2016|date=April 25, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Lemonade\">{{cite web|url=http://www.okayafrica.com/news/beyonce-lemonade-ibeyi-laolu-senbanjo-warsan-shire/|title=Ibeyi, Laolu Senbanjo, Warsan Shire Featured In Beyonc\u00e9's 'Lemonade'|publisher=Okay Africa|date=April 23, 2016|accessdate=April 23, 2016|author=Leaf, Aaron|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160425112002/http://www.okayafrica.com/news/beyonce-lemonade-ibeyi-laolu-senbanjo-warsan-shire/|archive-date=April 25, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> It also features [[Ibeyi]], [[Laolu Senbanjo]], [[Amandla Stenberg]], [[Quvenzhan\u00e9 Wallis]], [[Chloe x Halle]], [[Zendaya]] and [[Serena Williams]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/sportsperson/2015/12/14/serena-williams-si-sportsperson-year|title=Serena Williams is SI's Sportsperson of the Year|last=Price|first=S.L.|website=Sports Illustrated|access-date=April 25, 2016}}</ref> In \"[[Forward (song)|Forward]]\", the mothers of [[Trayvon Martin]] (Sybrina Fulton), [[Shooting of Michael Brown|Michael Brown]] (Lesley McFadden), and [[Death of Eric Garner|Eric Garner]] (Gwen Carr) are featured holding pictures of their deceased sons.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.essence.com/2016/04/24/trayvon-martin-michael-brown-eric-garner-mothers-beyonce-lemonade|title=Trayvon Martin, Michael Brown, and Eric Garner's Mothers Appear in Beyonc\u00e9's 'Lemonade' Video|date=April 24, 2016|website=Essence|accessdate=April 25, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160425111345/http://www.essence.com/2016/04/24/trayvon-martin-michael-brown-eric-garner-mothers-beyonce-lemonade|archive-date=April 25, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://time.com/4306316/beyonce-lemonade-black-woman-magic/|title=Beyonc\u00e9's Lemonade Is Black Woman Magic|last=Tinsley|first=Omise'eke Natasha|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|accessdate=April 25, 2016}}</ref> After \"[[Forward (song)|Forward]]\", a scene showcases a [[Mardi Gras Indians|Mardi Gras Indian]] circling a dining table, paying homage to the [[Culture of New Orleans|culture]] of [[New Orleans]], [[Louisiana]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/codeswitch/2016/04/27/475588107/the-mardi-gras-indian-of-lemonade|title=The Mardi Gras Indian Of 'Lemonade'|work=NPR.org|access-date=2018-02-02}}</ref> Jay-Z and Beyonc\u00e9's daughter [[Blue Ivy Carter|Blue Ivy]] appears in [[home video]] footage at one point, as does Jay-Z's grandmother Hattie White, and Beyonc\u00e9's mother [[Tina Knowles]], who is shown with her second husband [[Richard Lawson (actor)|Richard Lawson]] on their wedding day in 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/music/news/beyoncs-new-album-why-is-it-called-lemonade-plus-everything-else/|title=Beyonc\u00e9's new album: why is it called ''Lemonade'', what do the lyrics mean, plus all you need to know|newspaper=[[Telegraph (newspaper)|Telegraph]]|date=May 4, 2016|accessdate=November 6, 2016}}</ref> The film also samples work by [[Malcolm X]], specifically an excerpt from his speech \"Who Taught You to Hate Yourself\", which is featured on the track \"[[Don't Hurt Yourself (Beyonc\u00e9 song)|Don't Hurt Yourself]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mic.com/articles/141642/here-s-the-malcolm-x-speech-about-black-women-beyonce-sampled-in-lemonade#.l4Llrky2L|title=Here's the Malcolm X Speech About Black Women Beyonc\u00e9 Sampled in ''Lemonade''|publisher=Mic.com|accessdate=November 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn \"[[Hold Up (Beyonc\u00e9 song)|Hold Up]]\", Beyonc\u00e9 appears as [[Oshun]], a [[Yoruba culture|Yoruba]] water goddess of female sensuality, love and fertility. Oshun is often shown in yellow and surrounded by fresh water, and folktales of Oshun describe her malevolent temper and sinister smile when she has been wronged. Donning a flowing yellow [[Roberto Cavalli]] dress, gold jewelry and bare feet, Beyonc\u00e9 channels the [[orisha]], or goddess, by appearing in an underwater dreamlike state before emerging from two large golden doors with water rushing past her and down the stairs. During the \"Hold Up\" video, a smiling, laughing and dancing Beyonc\u00e9 smashes store windows, cars and cameras with a [[baseball bat]], representing Oshun's furious temper in a modern context. It also pays homage to artist [[Pipilotti Rist]]'s video installation \"Ever Is Over All\". \"[[Love Drought]]\" video features Beyonc\u00e9 leading a line of black women dressed in white along a shoreline. They stand, unified, looking out into the water as they hold hands and lift them one by one. This second reference to [[baptism]] is heavy in this scene along with messages of [[faith]] and [[love]], which are, the lyrics say, \"strong enough to move a mountain\" or \"end a drought\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/art/what-beyonce-teaches-us-about-the-african-diaspora-in-lemonade/|title=What Beyonc\u00e9 teaches us about the African diaspora in ''Lemonade''|publisher=PBS|date=April 29, 2016|accessdate=November 6, 2016}}</ref> Comparisons have also been drawn between the imagery of \"Love Drought\" and the [[Igbo Landing]], a historic location that was the site of a mass suicide by drowning of [[Igbo people]] who had been taken as slaves.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Owunna|first1=Mikael|title=Beyonc\u00e9's Love Drought Video, Slavery and the Story of Igbo Landing|url=http://owning-my-truth.com/post/143569446582/beyonces-lovedrought-video-slavery-igbolanding|accessdate=April 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2016, Matthew Fulks sued Beyonc\u00e9, [[Sony Music]], [[Columbia Records]] and [[Parkwood Entertainment]] for allegedly lifting elements of his short film ''Palinoia'' for ''Lemonade''. The lawsuit specifically targets the trailer for the HBO special.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr-esq/beyonce-sued-lemonade-trailer-900935|title=Beyonc\u00e9 Sued for Allegedly Lifting Short Film to Create 'Lemonade' Trailer|date=June 8, 2016|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=June 9, 2016|author=Gardner, Eriq}}</ref> Fulks had accused her of stealing nine visual elements from ''Palinoia''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/music/lawsuit-beyonce-lemonade-dropped-judge-article-1.2774447|title=Lawsuit against Beyonc\u00e9 for 'Lemonade' dropped by judge|newspaper=Daily News|location=New York|access-date=October 26, 2016}}</ref> The lawsuit was subsequently dismissed by New York federal judge [[Jed S. Rakoff]], siding with the defendant.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/judge-dismisses-lawsuit-against-beyonces-lemonade-w437735|title=Judge Dismisses Lawsuit Against Beyonc\u00e9's 'Lemonade'|last=Legaspi|first=Althea|date=September 1, 2016|work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=September 18, 2016}}</ref>\n\n{{multiple image\n | align  = left\n | image1 = Louisiana Superdome damage repair.jpg\n | width1 = 215\n | image2 = FtMacomb15FebE.jpg\n | width2 = 215\n | footer = Different locations were used to create Lemonade's film, including [[Mercedes-Benz Superdome]] (left) and [[Fort Macomb]] (right).<ref name=\"Fact Magazine\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.factmag.com/2016/04/27/lemonade-beyonce-meaning-visual-album/|title=Lemonade: The hidden meanings buried in Beyonc\u00e9\u2019s filmic journey through grief|magazine=[[Fact (UK magazine)|Fact Magazine]]|accessdate=October 9, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n=== Accolades ===\nThe film was nominated for four [[Primetime Emmy Award]]s, including [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Variety, Music, or Comedy Special|Outstanding Variety Special]] and [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Directing for a Variety Special|Outstanding Directing for a Variety Special]]. From the four categories, Beyonc\u00e9 was nominated in the aforementioned two.<ref name=\":15\" /> The album's visuals received eleven nominations at the [[2016 MTV Video Music Awards]], including [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Long Form Video|Breakthrough Long Form Video]] for ''Lemonade'', [[MTV Video Music Award for Video of the Year|Video of the Year]], [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Pop Video|Best Pop Video]], [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Direction|Best Direction]], [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Editing|Best Editing]], and [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]] for \"Formation\", [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Female Video|Best Female Video]] and [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Art Direction|Best Art Direction]] for \"Hold Up\", and [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Choreography|Best Choreography]] for \"Sorry\" and \"Formation\"; Beyonc\u00e9 won eight of her nominations.<ref name=\":16\" /> ''Lemonade'' won Best TV Show \u2013 Special or Limited Series at the [[African-American Film Critics Association Awards 2016]]<ref name=\":17\" /> and Outstanding Television Documentary or Special at the [[Black Reel Awards of 2017|2017 Black Reel Awards]].\n\nIn 2019, the ''Lemonade'' film was named the best music video of the decade (2010s) by ''[[The Daily Beast]]'',<ref name=\":19\" /> as well as one of the best movies of the decade by ''[[Vox Media|Vox]]''<ref name=\":20\" /> and the eleventh greatest film of the decade by ''[[Hyperallergic]]''.<ref name=\":21\" /> \n\n== Music and lyrics ==\n{{quote box\n| quote = We all experience pain and loss, and often we become inaudible. My intention for the film and album was to create a body of work that would give a voice to our pain, our struggles, our darkness and our history. To confront issues that make us uncomfortable. It\u2019s important to me to show images to my children that reflect their beauty, so they can grow up in a world where they look in the mirror, first through their own families \u2014 as well as the news, the [[Super Bowl]], the [[Olympics]], the [[White House]] and the [[Grammys]] \u2014 and see themselves, and have no doubt that they\u2019re beautiful, intelligent and capable. This is something I want for every child of every race. And I feel it\u2019s vital that we learn from the past and recognize our tendencies to repeat our mistakes.\n| source = \u2014Beyonc\u00e9 during her acceptance speech for the 2017 [[Grammy Award for Best Urban Contemporary Album]]<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite web|title=Beyonc\u00e9\u2019s and Adele\u2019s Grammy Speeches: Transcripts|website=New York Times|first=Giovanni|last=Russonello|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/12/arts/music/beyonce-speech-grammys-trump.html|date=Feb 12, 2017|accessdate=Apr 12, 2020}}</ref>\n| align = right\n| width = 30%\n| border = 1px\n| fontsize = 90%\n}}\nThe album features musicians [[Jack White]], [[Kendrick Lamar]], and bassist [[Marcus Miller]], and sampling from [[folk music]] collectors<ref name=\"Billboard1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7341787/beyonce-lemonade-album-features-the-weeknd-diplo-kendrick-lamar-more|title=Beyonc\u00e9's 'Lemonade': A Deep Dive Into the Star-Studded Album's Credits|last=Aswad|first=Jem|date=April 24, 2016|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=December 1, 2016}}</ref> [[John Lomax, Sr.]] and his son [[Alan Lomax]] on \"Freedom\". Beyonc\u00e9 and her team reference the musical memories of all those periods,<ref name=\"Billboard1\" /> including a [[Brass instrument|brass]] band, stomping [[blues rock]], ultraslow avant-R&B, preaching, a prison song (both collected by John and Alan Lomax), and the sound of the 1960s [[FuzzTone|fuzz-tone]] guitar psychedelia (sampling the Puerto Rican band Kaleidoscope).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/04/25/arts/music/beyonce-lemonade.html|title=Review: Beyonc\u00e9 Makes 'Lemonade' Out of Marital Strife|last=Pareles|first=Jon|date=April 24, 2016|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|issn=0362-4331|accessdate=April 25, 2016}}</ref>\nThe ''[[The Washington Post|Washington Post]]'' called the album a \"surprisingly furious [[song cycle]] about infidelity and revenge\",<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/beyonces-lemonade-turns-lifes-lemons-into-furious-pop/2016/04/24/cce58aec-0a4d-11e6-8ab8-9ad050f76d7d_story.html?tid=sm_tw|title=Beyonc\u00e9's 'Lemonade' turns life's lemons into furious pop|last=Richards|first=Chris|date=April 24, 2016|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|issn=0190-8286|access-date=April 25, 2016}}</ref> referencing the classical compositional genre defined in German [[lied]]er by [[Robert Schumann]], [[Franz Schubert]] and [[Johannes Brahms]]. The ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' described the album as not just a mere grab for [[popular music]] dominance, rather it is a retrospective that allows the listener to explore Beyonc\u00e9's personal circumstances, with musical tones from the [[southern United States]], a harkening back towards her formative years spent in [[Texas]].<ref name=\"Chicago Tribune\">{{cite web|last=Kot|first=Greg|title=Beyonc\u00e9's 'Lemonade' contains singer's most fully realized music yet|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/music/kot/ct-beyonce-lemonade-album-review-20160424-column.html|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=April 24, 2016|accessdate=April 25, 2016}}</ref> [[AllMusic]] wrote that Beyonc\u00e9 \"delights in her blackness, femininity, and Southern origin with supreme wordplay.\"<ref name=\"AllMusic Review\">{{cite web|first=Andy|last=Kellman|title=Lemonade \u2013 Beyonc\u00e9|website=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=April 20, 2019|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/lemonade-mw0002940342}}</ref>\n\nAccording to ''[[The A.V. Club]]'', the tracks \"encompass and interpolate the entire continuum of [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]], [[Rock music|rock]], [[Soul music|soul]], [[Hip hop music|hip hop]], [[Pop music|pop]], and [[blues]]\", accomplished by a deft precision \"blurring eras and references with determined impunity.\"<ref name=\"The A.V. Club\">{{cite web|first=Annie|last=Zaleski|title=Beyonc\u00e9's Lemonade pushes pop music into smarter, deeper places|url=http://www.avclub.com/review/beyonces-lemonade-pushes-pop-music-smarter-deeper--235819|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|accessdate=April 25, 2016|date=April 25, 2016}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'' and ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' both noted that the album touches on [[Country music|country]],<ref name=\"Entertainment Weekly\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/article/2016/04/27/beyonce-lemonade-ew-review|title=Beyonc\u00e9's Lemonade: EW Review|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|first=Ray|last=Rahman|date=April 27, 2016|accessdate=April 27, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite news|last=Petridis|first=Alexis|authorlink=Alexis Petridis|title=Beyonc\u00e9 \u2013 Lemonade review: 'A woman not to be messed with'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/apr/24/beyonce-lemonade-review-a-woman-not-to-be-messed-with|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=April 24, 2016|accessdate=April 24, 2016}}</ref> and ''Entertainment Weekly'' noticed the use of [[avant-garde music]]al elements. ''[[Consequence of Sound]]'' wrote that the album's genres span \"from [[Gospel music|gospel]] to rock to R&B to [[Trap music (hip hop)|trap]]\";<ref name=\"Consequence of Sound\">{{cite magazine|first=Britt|last=Julious|title=Beyonc\u00e9 \u2013 Lemonade|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/04/album-review-beyonce-lemonade/|magazine=[[Consequence of Sound]]|accessdate=April 30, 2016|date=April 29, 2016}}</ref> On the album, [[Isaac Hayes]] and [[Andy Williams]] are among the [[sampling (music)|sampled]] artists.<ref name=\"Entertainment Weekly\" />\n[[PopMatters]] noticed how the album was nuanced in its theme of anger and betrayal with vast swathes of the album bathed in political context; however, it is still a pop album at its essence with darker and praiseworthy tones.<ref name=\"PopMatters\">{{cite web|first=Evan|last=Sawdey|title=Beyonc\u00e9: Lemonade|url=http://www.popmatters.com/review/beyonce-lemonade/|work=[[PopMatters]]|accessdate=April 30, 2016|date=April 28, 2016}}</ref> [[Melina Matsoukas]], the director of the \"[[Formation (song)|Formation]]\" music video, said that Beyonc\u00e9 invited her to her house in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], and explained the concept behind ''Lemonade'', stating: \"She wanted to show the historical impact of [[slavery]] on black love, and what it has done to the black family, and black men and women\u2014how we're almost socialized not to be together.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/03/06/the-provocateur-behind-beyonce-rihanna-and-issa-rae|title=The Provocateur Behind Beyonc\u00e9, Rihanna, and Issa Rae|website=The New Yorker|access-date=February 18, 2017}}</ref> In an interview with ''[[W (magazine)|W]]'', Beyonc\u00e9's creative director Todd Tourso further explained the concept behind the album, referencing Beyonc\u00e9's desire of \"placing it in the context of a generational relationship\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wmagazine.com/story/the-secret-to-being-a-modern-pop-star-a-creative-director|title=The Secret to Being a Modern Pop Star? A Creative Director Pulling the Strings|website=[[W (magazine)|W]]|date=September 21, 2016|accessdate=May 29, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Title and artwork ==\nThe album title was inspired by Beyonc\u00e9's grandmother Agn\u00e9z Der\u00e9on, as well as her husband [[Jay-Z]]'s grandmother, Hattie White. At the end of the song \"Freedom\", an audio recording of Hattie White heard speaking to a crowd at her ninetieth birthday party in December 2015 is played. During the speech, Hattie says: \"I had my ups and downs, but I always find the inner strength to pull myself up. I was served lemons, but I made lemonade.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.popsugar.com.au/celebrity/Beyonce-Lemonade-Album-Meaning-41051485|title=Here's Why Beyonc\u00e9 Titled Her New Album Lemonade|last=Stephens|first=Brittney|website=POPSUGAR Celebrity Australia|access-date=April 24, 2016}}</ref> Streaming service [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]] described the concept behind ''Lemonade'' as \"every woman's journey of self-knowledge and healing.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/04/24/arts/music/beyonce-hbo-lemonade.html|title=Beyonc\u00e9 Releases Surprise Album 'Lemonade' After HBO Special|last=Coscarelli|first=Joe|date=April 23, 2016|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|accessdate=April 24, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe cover artwork for ''Lemonade'' features Beyonc\u00e9 standing next to a car, wearing a fur coat and [[cornrow]] braids, hiding her face behind her arm. It was shot during the filming of the music video for \"Don't Hurt Yourself\".\n\n== Release and promotion ==\n[[File:Formation recorte.jpg|thumb|Beyonc\u00e9 performing during [[The Formation World Tour]] at [[Carter\u2013Finley Stadium]] in [[Raleigh, North Carolina|Raliegh]], [[North Carolina]] on May 3, 2016]]\n\n=== Release ===\n''Lemonade'' was first made available for [[online streaming]] via [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]] on April 23, 2016 through [[Parkwood Entertainment]] and [[Columbia Records]], and for [[Music download|digital download]] the following day. It was released for [[Compact disc|CD]] and [[DVD]] on May 6, 2016. A [[limited edition]] [[box set]] titled ''How to Make Lemonade'' was made available for pre-order on August 18, 2017, containing a six-hundred-page [[coffee table book]], featuring a set of pictures and [[Making-of|behind-the-scenes]] content showcasing the making of the album, and a [[Gramophone record|double vinyl LP]] of ''Lemonade''. Standalone vinyl was released on September 15, 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.vogue.com/article/beyonce-how-to-make-lemonade-vogue-exclusive|title=Beyonc\u00e9 Just Released the Most Stylish 600-Page Coffee Table Book|work=Vogue|access-date=2017-08-29}}</ref> Upon its release, ''Lemonade'' was only available to stream on Tidal; however the album was eventually released to all other streaming platforms on April 23, 2019, exactly three years after its release. The version of the album that was made available on other streaming services contains the original audio part of ''Lemonade'' as well as the original demo of \"Sorry\".<ref name=\"Variety\">{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2019/music/news/beyonce-to-release-audio-of-lemonade-film-across-all-music-streaming-platforms-exclusive-1203191643/|title=Beyonce to Release Audio of \u2018Lemonade\u2019 Film across All Music Streaming Platforms (EXCLUSIVE)|work=Variety|access-date=2019-04-17}}</ref>\n\n=== Live performances ===\nBeyonc\u00e9 had a goal to perform the entire ''Lemonade'' album live.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/music/beyonce-choreographer-jaquel-knight-grammys-performance-motherhood-coachella/|title=Beyonc\u00e9's Choreographer Talks Grammys, Why Being a 'Great Mom' Informs Her Art \u2014 and If She'll 'Rock' Coachella|website=PEOPLE.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> Beyonc\u00e9 performed \"Formation\" at the [[Super Bowl 50 halftime show]] as part of her guest appearance at the event.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/02/08/sports/football/beyonce-coldplay-super-bowl-halftime-show.html|title=Review: It's Coldplay, Starring Beyonc\u00e9, at Super Bowl Halftime Show|last=Caramanica|first=Jon|date=February 7, 2016|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 29, 2017}}</ref> Beyonc\u00e9 performed \"[[Freedom (Beyonc\u00e9 song)|Freedom]]\" with [[Kendrick Lamar]] as the opening number at the [[BET Awards 2016|2016 BET Awards]] on June 27.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://time.com/4383201/beyonce-kendrick-freedom-bet-awards/|title=Watch Beyonc\u00e9 and Kendrick Lamar Destroy 'Freedom' At The BET Awards|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|first=Nash|last=Jankins|date=June 26, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016}}</ref> At the [[2016 MTV Video Music Awards]] on August 28, Beyonc\u00e9 performed a sixteen-minute medley of \"[[Pray You Catch Me]]\", \"[[Hold Up (Beyonc\u00e9 song)|Hold Up]]\", \"[[Sorry (Beyonc\u00e9 song)|Sorry]]\", \"[[Don't Hurt Yourself (Beyonc\u00e9 song)|Don't Hurt Yourself]]\", and \"[[Formation (song)|Formation]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/article/2016/08/28/vmas-beyonce-lemonade|title=VMAs 2016: Beyonc\u00e9 performs Lemonade tracks|last=Rosen|first=Christopher|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=August 28, 2016|accessdate=September 1, 2016}}</ref> The performance was ranked at number one on Andrew Unterberger's list of the \"100 Greatest Award Show Performances of All Time\" for ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/grammys/7677099/best-award-show-performances-of-all-time|title=The 100 Greatest Award Show Performances of All Time|date=February 8, 2017|first=Andrew|last=Unterberger|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=February 8, 2017}}</ref> On October 19, Beyonc\u00e9 performed \"[[6 Inch]]\" and \"[[All Night (Beyonc\u00e9 song)|All Night]]\" at the [[Tidal (service)|TIDAL X]] benefit concert at [[Barclays Center]] in [[Brooklyn]], [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.harpersbazaar.com/culture/art-books-music/news/a18325/beyonce-six-inch-tidal-performance/|title=Relive Beyonc\u00e9's \"6 Inch\" Performance from the TidalX: 1015 Concert Right Here|date=October 19, 2016|newspaper=Harper's BAZAAR|access-date=January 29, 2017}}</ref>\n\nA remix of \"[[Daddy Lessons]]\" featuring the [[Dixie Chicks]] was released as a [[promotional single]] on November 2, 2016 for free on Beyonc\u00e9's [[SoundCloud]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Daddy Lessons featuring the Dixie Chicks|url=https://soundcloud.com/beyonce/daddy-lessons-featuring-the-dixie-chicks|work=SoundCloud}}</ref> It previously debuted at number forty-one on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. Its music video was released on Tidal on November 5, 2016. On November 20, 2016, it was released on the [[iTunes Store]] for purchase and on all streaming services.<ref>{{cite web|title=Daddy Lessons (feat. Dixie Chicks) \u2013 Single|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/daddy-lessons-feat.-dixie/id1178163399|work=iTunes (US)}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Daddy Lessons \u2013 Beyonc\u00e9|url=https://play.spotify.com/album/7vmngE1EExuJ0wpdRescsX?play=true|work=Spotify}}</ref>\nOn November 2, Beyonc\u00e9 performed \"[[Daddy Lessons]]\" with the [[Dixie Chicks]] at the [[50th Annual Country Music Association Awards]] (2016).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.google.com/amp/www.billboard.com/amp/articles/columns/chart-beat/7564863/cma-awards-2016-beyonce-daddy-lessons-billboard-twitter-trending-140-chart|title=Beyonc\u00e9's 'Daddy Lessons' Tops Billboard + Twitter Trending 140 Chart After CMA Awards Performance|publisher=Google|accessdate=February 20, 2017}}</ref> Beyonc\u00e9 performed \"[[All Night (Beyonc\u00e9 song)|All Night]]\" in December 2016 at the [[Parkwood Entertainment]] Holiday Party. At the [[59th Annual Grammy Awards]] on February 12, 2017 Beyonc\u00e9 performed \"[[Love Drought]]\" and \"[[Sandcastles (song)|Sandcastles]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/71591-grammys-2017-watch-beyonces-incredible-performance/|title=Grammys 2017: Watch Beyonc\u00e9's Incredible Performance {{!}} Pitchfork|website=Pitchfork|access-date=February 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Tour ===\n{{Main|The Formation World Tour}}In order to promote the album, Beyonc\u00e9 embarked on [[The Formation World Tour]] which visited countries in North America and Europe from April to October 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/beyonce-stuns-with-lemonade-debuts-rousing-hits-at-tour-kickoff-20160428|title=Beyonc\u00e9 Stuns With 'Lemonade' Debuts, Rousing Hits at Tour Kickoff|work=Rolling Stone|first=Kat|last=Bein|date=April 28, 2016|accessdate=May 16, 2016}}</ref> The stage featured the [[Es Devlin]]-designed 'Monolith', a revolving seven-storey-tall box made with video screen walls that could shoot out fire and fireworks and split open, and which revolved during the show to represent a new chapter in line with the ''Lemonade'' film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://issuu.com/livedesignmagazine/docs/live_design_magazine_-_july_2016|title=Live Design Magazine July 2016|website=Issuu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://music.allaccess.com/beyonce-sells-out-dodger-stadium-on-formation-world-tour/|title=BEYONCE Sells Out Dodger Stadium on The Formation World Tour! {{!}} All Access Music|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nThe Formation World Tour was met with rave reviews from critics, such as Kat Bein for ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' who described the show as \"a prime example of entertainment and a vision of an artist at her apex\" and \"a visual feast as well as an emotional tour de force, packed with fireworks, confetti, rearranging stage designs and aerial dancers.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-live-reviews/beyonce-stuns-with-lemonade-debuts-rousing-hits-at-tour-kickoff-36078/|title=Beyonce Stuns With 'Lemonade' Debuts, Rousing Hits in Miami|last=Bein|first=Kat|last2=Bein|first2=Kat|date=2016-04-28|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> The Formation World Tour won [[American Music Award for Tour of the Year|Tour of the Year]] at the [[American Music Awards of 2016|2016 American Music Awards]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/events/amas/7581457/amas-2016-winners-list|title=AMAs 2016: Complete Winners List|date=2016-11-20|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> and was named the best tour of the decade (2010s) by [[Consequence of Sound|''Consequence of Sound'']] in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2019/11/top-25-tours-of-the-2010s/|title=Top 25 Tours of the 2010s|date=2019-11-08|website=Consequence of Sound|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\nThe Formation World Tour was ranked at number one and number two on ''[[Pollstar]]''<nowiki/>'s 2016 mid-year Top 100 Tours chart both in North America and worldwide respectively, with a total mid-year worldwide gross of $137.3 million from the first twenty-five shows (including $126.3 million from the first North American leg of the tour). In total, the tour grossed $256 million from forty-nine sold-out shows according to ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' box score, and ranked at number two on ''Pollstar''<nowiki/>'s 2016 Year-End Tours chart. \n== Singles ==\n\"[[Formation (song)|Formation]]\" was released as the album's lead [[Single (music)|single]] exclusively on Tidal on February 6, 2016, along with its accompanying music video. The following day, Beyonc\u00e9 performed it at the [[Super Bowl 50 halftime show]] as part of her guest appearance at the event.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/02/08/sports/football/beyonce-coldplay-super-bowl-halftime-show.html|title=Review: It's Coldplay, Starring Beyonc\u00e9, at Super Bowl Halftime Show|first=Jon|last=Caramanica|work=The New York Times|date=February 7, 2016|accessdate=May 16, 2016}}</ref> \"Formation\" peaked at number ten on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] and number six on the [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]]. The music video for the song was uploaded onto [[Vevo]] in December 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7350427/desiigner-drake-hot-100-prince-beyonce-top-10|title=Desiigner Holds Off Drake Atop Hot 100, Prince & Beyonc\u00e9 Hit Top 10|work=Billboard|date=May 2, 2016|first=Gary|last=Trust|accessdate=August 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\n\"[[Sorry (Beyonc\u00e9 song)|Sorry]]\" was released as the second single and serviced to [[rhythmic adult contemporary]] radio in the United States on May 3, 2016,<ref name=\"top40r\">{{cite web|title=Top 40 Rhythmic: Future Releases|url=http://www.allaccess.com/top40-rhythmic/future-releases|publisher=All Access|accessdate=May 2, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160502235807/http://www.allaccess.com/top40-rhythmic/future-releases|archivedate=May 2, 2016}}</ref> and its music video was uploaded onto Vevo on June 22, 2016.<ref>{{cite video|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QxsmWxxouIM|title=Beyonc\u00e9 \u2013 Sorry|publisher=[[Vevo]] on [[YouTube]]|date=June 22, 2016|accessdate=August 9, 2016}}</ref> The single debuted and peaked at number eleven on the US ''Billboard'' Hot 100.<ref name=\"BillboardSongPeaks\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/7350446/all-12-of-beyonces-lemonade-tracks-debut-on-hot-100|title=All 12 of Beyonc\u00e9's 'Lemonade' Tracks Debut on Hot 100|work=Billboard|first=Amaya|last=Mendizabal|date=May 2, 2016|accessdate=August 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\n\"[[Hold Up (song)|Hold Up]]\" was the third single and was first released to [[contemporary hit radio]] stations in Germany and the United Kingdom on May 12, 2016,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.wdr.de/radio/funkhauseuropa/musik/neuinfhe/beyonce-hold-up-100.html|title=Neu in Funkhaus Europa Beyonc\u00e9: \"Hold Up\"|work=[[Westdeutscher Rundfunk]]|accessdate=August 5, 2016|language=German|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160721034246/http://www1.wdr.de/radio/funkhauseuropa/musik/neuinfhe/beyonce-hold-up-100.html|archivedate=July 21, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio1/playlist|title=BBC \u2013 Radio 1 \u2013 Playlist|publisher=[[BBC Radio 1]]. [[BBC]]|accessdate=August 20, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160516151309/http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio1/playlist|archivedate=May 16, 2016}}</ref> and was later serviced to [[rhythmic contemporary]] radio in the United States on August 16, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fmqb.com/Article.asp?id=16691|title=FMQB: Radio Industry News, Music Industry Updates, Nielsen Ratings, Music News and more!|work=[[FMQB]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160804165226/http://www.fmqb.com/Article.asp?id=16691|archivedate=August 4, 2016|accessdate=August 4, 2016}}</ref> It debuted at number thirteen on the US ''Billboard'' Hot 100.<ref name=\"BillboardSongPeaks\" /> The music video for \"Hold Up\" was uploaded onto Vevo on September 4, 2016.<ref>{{cite video|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PeonBmeFR8o|title=Beyonc\u00e9 \u2013 Hold Up|publisher=[[Vevo]] on [[YouTube]]|date=September 4, 2016|accessdate=September 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\n\"[[Freedom (Beyonc\u00e9 song)|Freedom]]\" was released as the fourth single and was sent to radio stations on September 9, 2016. It previously peaked at number thirty-five on the US ''Billboard'' Hot 100.\n\n\"[[All Night (Beyonc\u00e9 song)|All Night]]\" was released as the fifth and final single on December 6, 2016. It previously debuted at number thirty-eight on the US ''Billboard'' Hot 100. Its accompanying music video was released onto Vevo on November 30, 2016.\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| MC = 92/100<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/lemonade/beyonce|title=Reviews for Lemonade by Beyonc\u00e9|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=April 25, 2016}}</ref>\n| ADM = 8.7/10<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.anydecentmusic.com/review/7971/Beyonce-Lemonade.aspx|title=Lemonade by Beyonc\u00e9 reviews|publisher=[[AnyDecentMusic?]]|accessdate=October 31, 2016}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{rating|4.5|5}}<ref name=\"AllMusic Review\" />\n| rev2 = ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"telegraph\" />\n| rev3 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev3Score = A+<ref name=\"Entertainment Weekly\"/>\n| rev4 = ''[[The Guardian]]''\n| rev4Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"guardian\" />\n| rev5 = ''[[The Independent]]''\n| rev5Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"the independent\" />\n| rev6 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev6Score = 4/5<ref name=\"NME\">{{cite web|last=Bartleet|first=Larry|title=Beyonc\u00e9 \u2013 'Lemonade' Review|url=http://www.nme.com/reviews/beyonce/16452|work=[[NME]]|date=April 25, 2016|accessdate=April 25, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160426121805/http://www.nme.com/reviews/beyonce/16452|archivedate=April 26, 2016}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev7Score = 8.5/10<ref name=\"Pitchfork Media\" />\n| rev8 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev8Score= {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"Rolling Stone\" />\n| rev9 = ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]''\n| rev9Score = 9/10<ref name=\"Spin\" />\n| rev10 = ''[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]'' ([[Robert Christgau#Consumer Guide|Expert Witness]])\n| rev10Score = A\u2212<ref>{{cite web|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|date=May 20, 2016|url=http://noisey.vice.com/blog/expert-witness-with-robert-christgau-beyonce-kevin-gates-azealia-banks|title=Baton Rouge, Big Beats, and Beyonc\u00e9: Expert Witness with Robert Christgau|work=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]|accessdate=July 17, 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n''Lemonade'' received widespread acclaim from [[Music journalism|music critics]] and is also the most critically acclaimed studio album of Beyonc\u00e9's career to date. In ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'', [[Greg Tate]] calls ''Lemonade'' \"a triumph of marketing and musicality, spectacle and song, vision and collaboration, [[Assimilation (Star Trek)|Borg-like assimilation]], and \u2014 as of 2013 \u2014 the element of surprise\". Lauding both the film and album, Tate writes \"Visually, literarily, choreographically, cinematically, this full accessing of her Southern bona fides shows up in the HBO project as ritual evidence that Bey\u2019s spent her downtime delving into the avant-garde mysticism of [[Black feminism|black-feminist]] poetry, novel writing, dance, gallery art, and film... The album, however, is out to sonorously suck you into its gully gravitational orbit the old fashioned way, placing the burden of conjuration on its steamy witches' brew of beats, melodies, and heavy-hearted-to-merry-pranksterish vocal seductions. In her mastery of carnal and esoteric mysteries, Queen Bey raises the spirits, sizzles the flesh, and rallies her troops.\"<ref name=\"Spin\">{{cite web|first=Greg|last=Tate|authorlink=Greg Tate|url=http://www.spin.com/2016/04/review-beyonce-lemonade/|title=Review: Beyonc\u00e9 Is the Rightful Heir to Michael Jackson and Prince on 'Lemonade'|work=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|accessdate=April 28, 2016|date=April 28, 2016}}</ref> [[AllMusic]] writer Andy Kellman called ''Lemonade'' \"culturally seismic\" through its \"layers of meaning and references, and experienced en masse through its televised premiere\", adding that \"the cathartic and wounded moments here resonate in a manner matched by few, if any, of Beyonc\u00e9's contemporaries.\"<ref name=\"AllMusic Review\" />\n\nIn a five-star review for ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', [[Rob Sheffield]] calls ''Lemonade'' \"a welcome reminder that giants still walk among us\", describing it as an \"album of emotional discord and marital meltdown... from the most respected and creative artist in the pop game\". Sheffield writes \"''Lemonade'' is her most emotionally extreme music, but also her most sonically adventurous... Yet the most astounding sound is always Bey\u2019s voice\", which is described as \"her wildest, rawest vocals ever\". Sheffield also compares ''Lemonade'' to [[Aretha Franklin]]\u2019s ''[[Spirit in the Dark]]'' and [[Nina Simone]]\u2019s ''[[Silk & Soul|Silk and Soul]]'' in the way that the album \"reach[es] out historically, connecting her personal pain to the trauma of American blackness\".<ref name=\"Rolling Stone\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/beyonce-lemonade-20160425|title=Lemonade|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|first=Rob|last=Sheffield|authorlink=Rob Sheffield|date=April 25, 2016|accessdate=April 26, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160531061410/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/beyonce-lemonade-20160425|archivedate=May 31, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Ray Rahman for ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' agrees, writing that ''Lemonade'' is \"a raw and intensely personal plunge into the heart of marital darkness\" as well as \"a feminist blueprint, a tribute to women, African-Americans, and, especially, African-American women\". Rahman further praises the diversity of the album: \"[Beyonc\u00e9] can do [[Rock music|rock]], [[blues]], [[Country music|country]], [[Avant-garde music|avant-garde]], whatever. ''Lemonade'' stands as Bey\u2019s most diverse album to date. Sinister strip-club-in-the-future [[Rhythm and blues|R&B]]... sits right next to a slab of Texas twang. [[Led Zeppelin]] and [[Soulja Boy]] become bedfellows.\"<ref name=\"Entertainment Weekly\" /> \n\n[[Alexis Petridis]] of ''[[The Guardian]]'' wrote that the album \"feels like a success\" and that Beyonc\u00e9 sounded \"genuinely imperious\". Petridis praises the musical arc of the album, commenting on how the music \"slowly works itself up into a righteous frenzy of anger, shifting from the becalmed misery of opener \"[[Pray You Catch Me]]\" via the sparse simmer of \"[[Hold Up (song)|Hold Up]]\"... before finally boiling over on the fantastic \"[[Don't Hurt Yourself (Beyonc\u00e9 song)|Don\u2019t Hurt Yourself]]\": a ferocious, distorted vocal as commanding as anything she\u2019s recorded\".<ref name=\"guardian\" /> ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' writer Jonathan Bernstein felt it was her strongest work to date and \"proves there's a thin line between love and hate.\"<ref name=\"telegraph\">{{cite news|last=Bernstein|first=Jonathan|title=Lemonade is Beyonc\u00e9 at her most profane, political and personal&nbsp;\u2014 review|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/music/what-to-listen-to/lemonade-is-beyonc-at-her-most-profane-political-and-personal/|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=April 24, 2016|accessdate=April 24, 2016}}</ref> Nekesa Moody and Mohamad Soliman from ''[[The Washington Post]]'' called the album a \"deeply personal, yet ... a bold social and political statement as well\".<ref name=\"twp\">{{cite news|last=Moody|first=Nekesa|title=Review: Beyonc\u00e9 again proves to be center of pop universe|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/music/review-beyonce-again-proves-to-be-center-of-pop-universe/2016/04/24/5caaf9ce-0a2f-11e6-bc53-db634ca94a2a_story.html|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=April 24, 2016|accessdate=April 24, 2016}}</ref> Writing for ''[[The New York Times]]'', [[Jon Pareles]] praised Beyonc\u00e9's vocals and her courage to talk about subjects that affect so many people, and noted that \"the album is not beholden to radio formats or presold by a single\".<ref name=\"nytimes\">{{cite web|last=Pareles|first=Jon|title=Review: Beyonc\u00e9 Makes 'Lemonade' Out of Marital Strife|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/04/25/arts/music/beyonce-lemonade.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=April 24, 2016|accessdate=April 24, 2016}}</ref> [[Greg Kot]] from the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' felt that \"artistic advances\" seem \"slight\" in context towards the record's \"more personal, raw and relatable\" aspects, where it came out as a \"clearly conceived\" piece of music, meaning it had a \"unifying vision\" for what may have lent itself to being \"a prettily packaged hodgepodge\".<ref name=\"Chicago Tribune\" />\n\nReviewing the album in ''[[The Independent]]'', [[Everett True]] wrote that it \"is fiery, insurgent, fiercely proud, sprawling and sharply focused in its dissatisfaction\", with Beyonc\u00e9 \"pick[ing] up the mantles of both\" [[Prince (musician)|Prince]] and [[Nina Simone]].<ref name=\"the independent\">{{cite web|last=True|first=Everett|authorlink=Everett True|title=Beyonc\u00e9, Lemonade review: Fiery, insurgent, fiercely proud, sprawling and sharply focused|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/beyonc-lemonade-review-fiery-insurgent-fiercely-proud-sprawling-and-sharply-focused-a7001291.html|work=[[The Independent]]|date=April 26, 2016|accessdate=April 26, 2016}}</ref> Writing for ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'', [[Carl Wilson (writer)|Carl Wilson]] describes ''Lemonade'' as \"a spectacle to rival ''[[Thriller (album)|Thriller]]''\" and \"a beautiful and often disturbing kaleidoscope of poetry, feminism, racial politics, history, mythology, emotional upheaval, family, and romance that can be watched again and again and will be for years to come\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://slate.com/culture/2016/04/beyonces-lemonade-is-incredible-as-a-visual-album-but-how-is-it-as-just-music.html|title=Beyonc\u00e9\u2019s Lemonade Is a Spectacle to Rival \u201cThriller.\u201d But How Is It as Strictly Music?|last=Wilson|first=Carl|date=2016-04-25|website=Slate Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Kitty Empire of ''[[The Observer]]'' writes that \"female endurance and pragmatism are celebrated with warmth, anger and wit on this astounding visual album\" and that \"it\u2019s unlikely there will be many more albums this year that will unite high art and low in the same way as Beyonc\u00e9\u2019s jaw-slackening latest\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Empire|first=Kitty|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/may/01/beyonce-lemonade-visual-album-review-woman-scorned|title=Beyonc\u00e9: Lemonade review \u2013 furious glory of a woman scorned|date=2016-05-01|work=The Observer|access-date=2020-03-22|language=en-GB|issn=0029-7712}}</ref> Jillian Mapes of ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' wrote that \"The increasingly signature cadence, patois, and all-around attitude on ''Lemonade'' speaks to her status as the hip-hop pop star\u2014but this being Bey, she doesn\u2019t stop there... ''Lemonade'' proves Beyonc\u00e9 to also be a new kind of post-genre pop star\".<ref name=\"Pitchfork Media\">{{cite web|first=Jillian|last=Mapes|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/21867-lemonade/|title=Beyonc\u00e9: Lemonade|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|accessdate=April 26, 2016|date=April 26, 2016}}</ref> In ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' Annie Zaleski wrote that it was \"yet another seismic step forward for Beyonc\u00e9 as a musician\" that \"pushes pop music into smarter, deeper places\".<ref name=\"The A.V. Club\" />\n\nShahzaib Hussain, writing for ''[[Clash (magazine)|Clash]]'', stated: \"''Lemonade'' is Beyonc\u00e9 at her most benevolent, and her most unadulterated. Treating her blackness not as an affliction but a celebratory beacon, ''Lemonade'' is a long overdue, cathartic retribution.\"<ref name=\"clash\">{{cite web|first=Shahzaib|last=Hussain|url=http://clashmusic.com/reviews/beyonc%C3%A9-lemonade|title=Beyonc\u00e9 \u2013 Lemonade|work=[[Clash (magazine)|Clash]]|accessdate=April 26, 2016|date=April 26, 2016}}</ref> Sal Cinquemani of ''[[Slant Magazine]]'' wrote that the album \"is her most lyrically and thematically coherent effort to date.\"<ref name=\"Slant Magazine\">{{cite web|first=Sal|last=Cinquemani|title=Beyonc\u00e9: ''Lemonade''|work=[[Slant Magazine]]|date=April 25, 2016|accessdate=April 26, 2016|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/beyonce-lemonade}}</ref> [[Maura Johnston]] of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' wrote that its tracks were \"fresh yet instantly familiar\" with an \"over-the-top but intimate\" sound.<ref name=\"time magazine\">{{cite news|first=Maura|last=Johnston|url=http://time.com/4305890/beyonce-lemonade-album-review/|title=Review: Beyonc\u00e9 Makes Lemonade From Romantic Strife on Her New Album|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|accessdate=April 26, 2016|date=April 24, 2016}}</ref> Jamie Milton of ''[[DIY (magazine)|DIY]]'' wrote that \"there's so much more than an enthralling story to draw out of this all-slaying work\", where \"Beyonc\u00e9 can count herself as a risk-taker breaking new ground, up there with the bravest.\"<ref name=\"DIY magazine\">{{cite web|first=Jamie|last=Milton|url=http://diymag.com/2016/04/27/beyonce-lemonade-album-review|title=Album Review: Beyonc\u00e9 \u2013 Lemonade|work=[[DIY (magazine)|DIY]]|accessdate=April 27, 2016|date=April 27, 2016}}</ref> ''[[Exclaim!]]''{{'}}s Erin Lowers wrote that \"If you've ever been handed lemons, you need ''Lemonade''\", calling it \"an album in which millions will find their own struggles reflected back to them, as therapeutic as it is utterly dazzling\".<ref name=\"Exclaim!\">{{cite web|last=Lowers|first=Erin|title=Beyonc\u00e9: Lemonade|url=http://exclaim.ca/music/article/beyonc_-lemonade|work=[[Exclaim!]]|date=April 28, 2016|accessdate=April 27, 2016}}</ref> Britt Julious of [[Consequence of Sound|''Consequence of Sound'']] describes how \"With nods to [[Louisiana Voodoo|Voudou]] and Southern Black gothic storytelling, ''Lemonade'', the visual album, wove chapters of emotional grief into a piece of art about the black woman... Separated from the visual, the album itself acts as dexterously as the film, exposing the rawest elements of Beyonc\u00e9\u2019s personal life while framing it against the universal \u2014 the machinations of internal paranoia, the all-consuming well of fury and anger, and the bottomless depths of sadness.\" Julious continues by praising the [[song cycle]] nature of the album: \"Taken as a whole, we hear the threads of this from song to song on the record. If ''Lemonade'' is a record about dismantling the cycles of abuse, ripping open the secrets we keep hidden (especially within the closely guarded black community), and finding healing, purpose, and even greatness in the process, then it is personified in the arcs of each track... The songs stand as joined entities, two dichotomous halves of the grief process\".<ref name=\"Consequence of Sound\" /> [[PopMatters]] writer Evan Sawdey felt few albums could ever be considered \"as bold, complex, or resolute as ''Lemonade'',\"<ref name=\"PopMatters\" /> and the [[BBC]]'s Mark Savage, describing ''Lemonade'' as \"an album with a complex narrative arc... that demands to be heard in one sitting\", noted that Beyonc\u00e9 had become an albums artist with a range extending beyond that of radio play.<ref name=\"Albums artist.\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-36160506|title=How Beyonce became an 'albums artist' \u2013 and what radio is doing about it|publisher=BBC|accessdate=May 4, 2016|author=0}}</ref>\n\n==Accolades==\n===Publications===\nAt the end of 2016, ''Lemonade'' appeared on a number of critics' lists ranking the year's top albums. According to [[Metacritic]], it was the second most prominently ranked record of 2016, and the album that was listed at number 1 by the most publications (37 publications).<ref>{{cite web|last=Dietz|first=Jason|date=November 28, 2016|url=http://www.metacritic.com/feature/critics-pick-top-10-best-albums-of-2016|title=Best of 2016: Music Critic Top Ten Lists|website=Metacritic|accessdate=December 11, 2016}}</ref> ''Lemonade'' was ranked as the best album of the year by such publications as ''[[Rolling Stone]]'',<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/50-best-albums-of-2016-w451265/david-bowie-blackstar-w451267|title=50 Best Albums of 2016|date=November 28, 2016|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=November 28, 2016}}</ref> ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/photos/7597536/billboards-50-best-albums-of-2016-critics-picks/14|title=Billboard's 50 Best Albums of 2016: Critics' Picks|work=Billboard|accessdate=February 20, 2017}}</ref> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'',<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/article/2016/12/08/ew-best-albums-2016/5|title=The 50 best albums of 2016|date=December 8, 2016|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=December 8, 2016}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/nov/30/the-best-albums-of-2016|title=The best albums of 2016: the full list|date=November 30, 2016|accessdate=February 20, 2017|via=The Guardian}}</ref> ''[[Digital Spy]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/music/feature/a816398/best-albums-of-2016/|title=20 best albums of 2016: Who have we crowned No.1?|date=December 29, 2016|work=Digital Spy|accessdate=February 20, 2017}}</ref> ''[[The Independent]]'',<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/features/best-albums-2016-beyonce-anderson-paak-frank-ocean-leonard-cohen-chance-the-rapper-a7446336.html|title=Best albums of 2016: Our 20 favourite releases from an incredible year of music|last=O'Connor|first=Roisin|date=November 30, 2016|work=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=December 1, 2016}}</ref> ''[[The Associated Press]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/a134cc1f443e4660ae8a9da212c4d95b/aps-top-albums-2016-beyonce-rihanna-solange-bruno|title=AP's top albums of 2016: Beyonc\u00e9, Rihanna, Solange, Bruno|work=Associated Press|accessdate=February 20, 2017}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' ([[Jon Pareles]] list),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/07/arts/music/best-albums.html|title=The Best Albums of 2016|date=December 7, 2016|work=The New York Times|accessdate=February 20, 2017}}</ref> ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' (Mikael Wood list),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-ca-ms-year-in-pop-music-mikael-wood-20161215-story.html|title=The 10 best albums of a year defined by loss|first=Mikael|last=Wood|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=February 20, 2017}}</ref> ''[[Pop Matters]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.popmatters.com/feature/the-70-best-albums-of-2016/P6/|title=The 70 Best Albums of 2016|work=PopMatters|accessdate=February 20, 2017}}</ref> ''Pretty Much Amazing'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://prettymuchamazing.com/features/best-albums-2016|title=The 60 Best Albums of 2016|publisher=prettymuchamazing.com|accessdate=February 20, 2017}}</ref> [[Idolator (website)|Idolator]],<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.idolator.com/featured/best-albums-2016-beyonce-solange-frank-ocean-rihanna-kanye-west-bruno-mars|title=The 10 Best Albums Of 2016|date=December 6, 2016|work=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]|accessdate=December 6, 2016}}</ref> ''[[Stereogum]]'',<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.stereogum.com/featured/the-50-best-albums-of-2016/|title=The 50 Best Albums Of 2016|date=December 1, 2016|publisher=stereogum.com|accessdate=February 20, 2017}}</ref> ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]'',<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/music/best-albums-of-2016/beyonce-lemonade|title=The 50 Best Albums of 2016|date=December 5, 2016|work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|accessdate=December 5, 2016}}</ref> ''[[Consequence of Sound]]'',<ref name=\":6\">{{cite web|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/11/top-50-albums-of-2016/|title=Top 50 Albums of 2016|date=November 28, 2016|work=[[Consequence of Sound]]|accessdate=November 28, 2016}}</ref> ''[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/wireds-albums-of-2016|title=WIRED's top 16 albums of 2016|date=December 17, 2016|last=Lott-Lavigna|first=Ruby|work=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]|accessdate=December 17, 2016}}</ref> and ''[[US Weekly]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/entertainment/news/beyonces-lemonade-is-us-best-album-of-2016-read-the-full-list-w456112|title=Beyonc\u00e9\u2019s \u2018Lemonade\u2019 Is Us\u2019 Best Album of 2016: Read the Full List!|work=Us Weekly|accessdate=February 20, 2017}}</ref> ''[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]'',<ref name=\":7\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2016/11/the-50-best-albums-of-2016.html|title=The 50 Best Albums of 2016|date=November 30, 2016|work=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]|accessdate=November 30, 2016}}</ref> ''[[USA Today]],''<ref name=\":8\">{{cite web|url=http://ftw.usatoday.com/2016/12/the-50-best-albums-of-2016|title=The 50 best albums of 2016|date=December 6, 2016|work=USA Today|accessdate=February 20, 2017}}</ref> ''[[NPR]]'' also included the release on their list of best albums of 2016.<ref name=\":9\">{{cite web|url=http://apps.npr.org/best-music-2016/list/top-albums/|title=Best 50 Albums of 2016|publisher=NPR|accessdate=February 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn the annual ''[[Village Voice]]''{{'}}s Pazz & Jop mass critics poll of the year's best in music in 2016, ''Lemonade'' was ranked at number two.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.villagevoice.com/pazznjop/albums/2016|title=PAZZ+JOP 2016|work=The Village Voice|date=January 25, 2017|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> For ''[[Slant (magazine)|Slant]]'' it was the third best,<ref name=\":10\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2016/11/the-50-best-albums-of-2016.html|title=The 25 Best Albums of 2016|date=December 8, 2016|work=[[Slant (magazine)|Slant]]|accessdate=December 8, 2016}}</ref> while ''[[Exclaim!]]'' listed the album at number four on their list of the Top 20 Pop & Rock Albums of 2016.<ref name=\":11\">{{cite web|url=http://exclaim.ca/music/article/exclaim_s_top_20_pop_and_rock_albums_part_two-best_of_2016/page/8|title=Exclaim!'s Top 20 Pop & Rock Albums, Part Two Best of 2016- Page 8 of 11|work=Exclaim!|accessdate=February 20, 2017}}</ref> According to ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'', it was the sixth best album of 2016.<ref name=\":12\">{{cite web|url=http://www.spin.com/featured/the-50-best-albums-of-2016/|title=The 50 Best Albums of 2016|date=December 12, 2016|work=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|accessdate=December 12, 2016}}</ref> ''[[NME (magazine)|NME]]'' listed ''Lemonade'' at number eleven on their list of best albums of the year,<ref name=\":13\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/list/nme-best-albums-2016-1869261|title=NME's Albums of the Year 2016|date=November 24, 2016|work=[[NME (magazine)|NME]]|accessdate=November 24, 2016}}</ref> ''[[Fact (UK magazine)|FACT]]'' at number fifteen,<ref name=\":14\">{{cite web|url=http://www.factmag.com/2016/12/13/best-albums-of-2016/|title=The 50 best albums of 2016|date=December 13, 2016|work=[[Fact (UK magazine)|FACT]]|accessdate=December 13, 2016}}</ref> ''[[Drowned in Sound]]'' at number twelve,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://drownedinsound.com/in_depth/4150679-drowned-in-sounds-16-favourite-albums-of-2016|title=Drowned in Sound's 16 Favourite Albums of 2016|work=Drowned in Sound|accessdate=February 20, 2017}}</ref> ''[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]'' at number ten,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uncut.co.uk/features/best-albums-2016-uncut-top-50-98681|title=The Best Albums Of 2016 \u2013 The Uncut Top 50 \u2013 Uncut|date=December 20, 2016|work=Uncut|accessdate=February 20, 2017}}</ref> ''[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]'' at number twelve,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/mojoend.html#2016|title=Rocklist.net...Mojo End Of year Lists...|publisher=rocklistmusic.co.uk|accessdate=February 20, 2017}}</ref> ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]'' at number thirteen,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/qlists.html#2016|title=Rocklist.net...Q magazine Recordings Of The Year|publisher=rocklistmusic.co.uk|accessdate=February 20, 2017}}</ref> while ''[[Tiny Mix Tapes]]'' at number thirty-two.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tinymixtapes.com/features/2016-favorite-50-music-releases?page=1|title=2016: Favorite 50 Music Releases|publisher=tinymixtapes.com|accessdate=February 20, 2017}}</ref> ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'' magazine included ''Lemonade'' among the twenty best releases of 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.esquire.co.uk/culture/reviews/g9818/best-albums-of-year-2016-music-review/|title=The 20 Best Albums Of 2016|work=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]|publisher=[[Hearst (media)|Hearst]]|accessdate=November 24, 2016}}</ref> ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' listed ''Lemonade'' at number one on their list of best music videos of 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/features/lists-and-guides/9979-the-best-music-videos-of-2016/?page=3|title=The Best Music Videos of 2016|date=November 28, 2016|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|accessdate=December 1, 2016}}</ref> The publication would later name ''Lemonade'' the third best album of the same year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/features/lists-and-guides/9980-the-50-best-albums-of-2016/?page=5|title=The 50 Best Albums of 2016|date=December 13, 2016|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|accessdate=December 13, 2016}}</ref>\nIt was also included on ''[[Sight & Sound]]''{{'}}s best films of 2016 list at number twenty-six.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/best-films-2016|title=The best films of 2016|date=December 2, 2016|work=[[Sight & Sound]]|publisher=[[British Film Institute]]|accessdate=December 2, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/browbeat/2016/12/02/the_sight_sound_poll_picks_the_best_movies_of_2016_beyonc_s_lemonade_among.html|title=Beyonc\u00e9's Lemonade Makes Sight & Sound's Best Films of 2016|last=Adams|first=Sam|date=December 2, 2016|work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]|publisher=[[The Slate Group]]|accessdate=December 2, 2016}}</ref> David Ehrlich, a film critic for [[IndieWire]], placed ''Lemonade'' at number twenty-three on his Best Films of 2016 list.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiewire.com/2016/12/best-movies-2016-david-ehrlich-memorable-moments-1201753085/|title=The Best Movies Of 2016, According To IndieWire Critic David Ehrlich \u2013 IndieWire|first=David|last=Ehrlich|publisher=indiewire.com|accessdate=February 20, 2017}}</ref> Jen Yamato from ''[[The Daily Beast]]'' ranked it at number nine on her list of the Top 10 Best Films of 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2016/12/14/the-10-best-films-of-2016-beyonce-killer-neo-nazis-and-a-modern-day-masterpiece.html|title=The 10 Best Films of 2016: Beyonc\u00e9, Killer Neo-Nazis, and a Modern-Day Masterpiece|first=Jen|last=Yamato|date=December 14, 2016|publisher=thedailybeast.com|accessdate=February 20, 2017}}</ref> \n\n''Lemonade'' was named the best album of the decade (2010s) by ''[[Consequence of Sound]]'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2019/11/top-albums-of-the-2010s/4/|title=Top 100 Albums of the 2010s|date=November 4, 2019|website=Consequence of Sound|accessdate=November 4, 2019}}</ref>  ''[[The Associated Press]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/d66d82c5f7182b087f88b4e787e33073|title=\u2018Lemonade\u2019 by Beyonc\u00e9 is named the AP\u2019s album of the decade|date=December 12, 2019|website=Associated Press|accessdate=December 13, 2019}}</ref> and ''[[Spex (magazine)|Spex]]''.<ref>{{cite magazine|date=December 20, 2019|title=Die besten Alben 2010-2019: Platz 3-1|url=https://spex.de/die-besten-alben-2010-2019-platz-3-1/|magazine=[[Spex (magazine)|Spex]]|accessdate=December 20, 2019}}</ref> ''Lemonade'' was also named the best music video of the decade by ''[[The Daily Beast]]'',<ref name=\":19\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/the-10-best-music-videos-of-the-decade|title=The 10 Best Music Videos of the Decade|last=Costa|first=Cassie da|date=2019-12-29|access-date=2019-12-30|language=en}}</ref> as well as one of the best movies of the 2010s by ''[[Vox Media|Vox]]''<ref name=\":20\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/culture/2019/12/17/21012868/lemonade-beyonce-best-films-decade-2010s|title=Beyonc\u00e9\u2019s Lemonade is one of the best movies of the 2010s|last=Wilkinson|first=Alissa|date=2019-12-17|website=Vox|language=en|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref> and the eleventh greatest film of the decade by ''[[Hyperallergic]]''.<ref name=\":21\">{{Cite web|url=https://hyperallergic.com/533427/best-films-of-the-2010s/|title=The Best Films of the Decade|date=2019-12-23|website=Hyperallergic|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref> ''[[Rolling Stone]]''<ref>{{cite magazine|date=3 December 2019|title=The 100 Best Albums of the 2010s|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/best-albums-2010s-ranked-913997/?list_page=2|accessdate=3 December 2019|website=[[Rolling Stone]]}}</ref> ''[[The Independent]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/features/best-albums-decade-2010s-frank-ocean-adele-taylor-swift-kanye-west-ranked-a9204121.html|title=The 50 best albums of the decade, from Frank Ocean\u2019s \u2018Blond\u2019 to Adele\u2019s \u201821\u2019|date=18 November 2019|website=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=December 3, 2019}}</ref> ''[[New York Post]]'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2019/12/27/best-albums-of-the-decade-kanye-west-beyonce-top-the-list/|title=Best albums of the decade: Kanye West, Beyonc\u00e9 top the list|last=Arnold|first=Chuck|date=2019-12-27|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref> ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]],''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/list/8543722/best-albums-of-the-2010s-top-100|title=The 100 Greatest Albums of the 2010s: Staff Picks|date=November 19, 2019|website=Billboard|accessdate=December 3, 2019}}</ref> ''[[Paste Magazine]],''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2019/10/best-albums-of-the-2010s-paste.html?p=4|title=The 100 Best Albums of the Decade|date=October 9, 2019|website=Paste Magazine|accessdate=October 9, 2019}}</ref> ''[[The A.V. Club]],''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://music.avclub.com/the-50-best-albums-of-the-2010s-1839776060|title=The 50 best albums of the 2010s|date=November 20, 2019|website=The A.V. Club|accessdate=December 3, 2019}}</ref> ''[[WXPN]] The Key'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thekey.xpn.org/2019/12/02/the-25-best-albums-of-the-decade/|title=The 25 Best Albums of the Decade, 2010-2019|date=2019-12-02|website=The Key|language=en|access-date=2019-12-23}}</ref> and ''[[Refinery29]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.refinery29.com/en-us/2019/12/9018628/best-albums-2010s-decade|title=Women Ruled Music In The 2010s & The 10 Best Albums Of The Decade Prove It|last=Smith|first=Courtney E.|website=www.refinery29.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-23}}</ref> declared ''Lemonade'' the second best album of the 2010s. ''Lemonade'' was named the third best album of the decade by ''[[Tampa Bay Times]],''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tampabay.com/arts-entertainment/music/2019/12/26/the-10-best-albums-of-the-2010s-kanye-kendrick-beyonce-and-more/|title=The 10 best albums of the 2010s: Kanye, Kendrick, Beyonce and more|website=Tampa Bay Times|language=en|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref> ''[[Insider Inc.|Insider]]'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insider.com/best-albums-artists-2010s-decade-2019-12|title=15 of the best albums of the decade, ranked|last=Larocca|first=Courteney|website=Insider|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref> and ''The Young Folks,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theyoungfolks.com/music/137777/the-young-folks-top-50-albums-of-the-2010s/|title=The Young Folks' Top 50 Albums of the 2010s {{!}} The Young Folks|date=2019-11-05|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-23}}</ref>'' while the ''[[Genius (website)|Genius]]'' community<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genius.com/a/the-genius-communitys-100-best-albums-of-the-2010s|title=The Genius Community\u2019s 100 Best Albums of the 2010s|website=Genius|language=en|access-date=2019-12-23}}</ref> and Chris Willman for ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/feature/best-albums-decade-2010-2019-1203444452/|title=The Best Albums of the Decade|last=Willman|first=Andrew Barker,Jem Aswad,Chris|last2=Barker|first2=Andrew|date=2019-12-20|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2019-12-30|last3=Aswad|first3=Jem|last4=Willman|first4=Chris}}</ref>'' named it the fourth best one. ''[[Uproxx]],''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://uproxx.com/music/best-albums-2010s-ranked-decade/|title=The 100 Best Albums Of The 2010s, Ranked|date=2019-10-07|website=UPROXX|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-23}}</ref> ''[[Noisey]],''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/qvg5j3/the-100-best-albums-of-the-2010s|title=The 100 Best Albums of the 2010s|last=Staff|first=Alex Jenkins,VICE|date=2019-11-06|website=Vice|language=en|access-date=2019-12-23}}</ref> ''[[The Independent]],''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/features/best-albums-decade-2010s-frank-ocean-adele-taylor-swift-kanye-west-ranked-a9204121.html|title=The 50 best albums of the decade|date=2019-11-18|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2019-12-23}}</ref> and ''The Wild Honey Pie''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thewildhoneypie.com/playlists/top-50-albums-of-the-2010s|title=Top 50 Albums of the 2010s|last=P22.studio|website=The Wild Honey Pie|language=en|access-date=2019-12-23}}</ref> named ''Lemonade'' the fifth best album of the decade. ''Pitchfork'' listed ''Lemonade'' as the 41st greatest album of the decade.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/features/lists-and-guides/the-200-best-albums-of-the-2010s/|title=The 200 Best Albums of the 2010s|website=Pitchfork|date=October 8, 2019|accessdate=October 8, 2019}}</ref> ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5725768/best-albums-2010s-decade/|title=The 10 Best Albums of the 2010s|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2019-12-23}}</ref> [[Paper (magazine)|''Paper'']],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.papermag.com/paper-top-10-albums-decade-2641630072.html|title=PAPER's Top 10 Albums of the '10s|date=2019-12-21|website=PAPER|language=en|access-date=2019-12-23}}</ref> [[Stuff (website)|''Stuff'']],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/music/117962613/from-lorde-to-kanye-via-billie-eilish--the-10-best-albums-of-the-decade|title=From Lorde to Kanye, via Billie Eilish - the 10 best albums of the decade|website=Stuff|language=en|access-date=2019-12-23}}</ref> and ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/culture/music/kanye-beyonce-taylor-billie-the-albums-of-the-decade-20191205-p53h5n.html|title=Kanye, Beyonce, Taylor, Billie: The albums of the decade|last=Mathieson|first=Craig|date=2019-12-07|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2019-12-23}}</ref> included the album in their lists of the best 10 albums of the decade. ''Lemonade'' was included in ''[[The Atlantic]]''<nowiki/>'s \"Time Capsule of the 2010s\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2019/12/pop-culture-time-capsule-2010s/604261/|title=A Time Capsule of the 2010s|last=Desk|first=The Atlantic Culture|date=2019-12-31|website=The Atlantic|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref> ''Lemonade'' was included in ''[[Triple J]]'''s top 15 biggest music moments of the decade list.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/triplej/news/musicnews/biggest-music-moments-of-the-decade-2010s-australia/11962236|title=Biggest music moments of the 2010s|last=Newstead|first=Al|date=2020-02-15|website=triple j|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\n''Lemonade'' is the 20th best album of all time by ''[[Metacritic]]'' score.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/browse/albums/score/metascore/all/filtered|title=Best Music and Albums of All Time|website=Metacritic|language=en|access-date=2019-12-23}}</ref> ''[[BBC Radio 4]]''<nowiki/>'s named ''Lemonade'' the eighth greatest risk in 21st century art, with the judges saying that Beyonc\u00e9 \"resisted the commercial pressure not to be political in order to stand up for what she believed in and let audiences into her personal life as never before\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/2sMsFVDBBRN3CjHmy2Xm1DM/the-10-biggest-risks-in-21st-century-art|title=BBC Radio 4 - Front Row - The 10 Biggest Risks in 21st Century Art|website=BBC|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'' listed it at number 25 on their ranking of the 100 best albums of the 21st century.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/sep/13/100-best-albums-of-the-21st-century|title=The 100 best albums of the 21st century|website=The Guardian|date=September 13, 2019|accessdate=October 9, 2019}}</ref> On their list of the top 100 albums of the publication's existence, ''[[The Quietus]]'' named the project at number 9.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thequietus.com/articles/25381-top-100-albums-of-the-quietus-existence-2008-2018-decade|title=The Top 100 Albums Of The Quietus' Existence, As Picked By tQ's Writers|website=theQuietus|date=October 3, 2018|accessdate=October 9, 2019}}</ref> In 2017, the album was ranked at number 6 on ''[[NPR]]''{{'}}s list of the 150 Greatest Albums Made By Women.<ref>{{cite web|title=The 150 Greatest Albums Made By Women|url=https://www.npr.org/2017/07/20/538307314/turning-the-tables-150-greatest-albums-made-by-women-page-15|website=NPR.org|accessdate=July 25, 2017}}</ref> \n\n===Awards===\n\"Formation\" won in three categories at the [[BET Awards 2016|2016 BET Awards]] for [[BET Award for Video of the Year|Video of the Year]], the [[BET Centric Award|Centric Award]], and the [[BET Award for Viewer's Choice|Viewers Choice Award]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/music/awards/bet-awards-2016-winners-list-1201803903/|title=BET Awards 2016: Full BET Winners List|work=Variety|date=June 26, 2016|accessdate=September 1, 2016}}</ref> At the [[BET Awards 2017|2017 BET Awards]] Beyonc\u00e9 was nominated in 7 categories and won 5, including [[BET Award for Video of the Year|Album of the Year]], [[BET Award for Video of the Year|Video of the Year]] for \"[[Sorry (Beyonc\u00e9 song)|Sorry]]\" and [[BET Award for Best R&B Artists|Best Female R&B/Pop Artist]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/bet-awards-full-list-winners-1015961/item/bet-awards-noms-best-male-r-b-pop-artist-1003778|title=Best Male R&B/Pop Artist - BET Awards: Beyonce Tops Winners With 5|website=hollywoodreporter.com|accessdate=June 28, 2017}}</ref> The ''Lemonade'' film was nominated for four [[Primetime Emmy Award]]s, including [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Variety, Music, or Comedy Special|Outstanding Variety Special]] and [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Directing for a Variety Special|Outstanding Directing for a Variety Special]]. From the four categories, Beyonc\u00e9 was nominated in the two mentioned.<ref name=\":15\">{{cite web|url=http://www.emmys.com/sites/default/files/Downloads/68th-nominations-list-v2.pdf|title=68th Emmy Awards Nominations For Programs Airing June 1, 2015 including 2016|publisher=[[Academy of Television Arts & Sciences|The Television Academy]]|date=July 14, 2016|accessdate=July 14, 2016}}</ref> The album's visuals received 11 nominations at the [[2016 MTV Video Music Awards]]. They included [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Long Form Video|Breakthrough Long Form Video]] for ''Lemonade'', [[MTV Video Music Award for Video of the Year|Video of the Year]], [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Pop Video|Best Pop Video]], [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Direction|Best Direction]], [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Editing|Best Editing]], and [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]] for \"Formation\", [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Female Video|Best Female Video]] and [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Art Direction|Best Art Direction]] for \"Hold Up\", and [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Choreography|Best Choreography]] for \"Sorry\" and \"Formation\".<ref name=\":16\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/events/vma/7453279/beyonce-adele-lead-nominees-2016-mtv-video-music-awards|title=Beyonc\u00e9, Adele Lead Nominees for 2016 MTV Video Music Awards|work=Billboard|accessdate=July 26, 2016}}</ref> Beyonc\u00e9 went on to win eight of her nominations, including Video of the Year and Breakthrough Long Form Video.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/events/vma/7487873/vmas-2016-winners-list|title=VMAs 2016 Winners List|work=Billboard|date=August 28, 2016|accessdate=September 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\nShe received two nominations at the 2016 [[MTV Video Music Awards Japan]] for [[MTV Video Music Award Japan for Album of the Year|Best Album of the Year]] for ''Lemonade'' and [[MTV Video Music Award Japan for Best Female Video|Best Female Video International]] for \"Formation\", eventually winning for Best Album of the Year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtvjapan.com/vmaj2016/nominees/best-album/beyonce/|title=Beyonc\u00e9 \u2013 Best Album of the Year|publisher=[[MTV Japan]]|accessdate=September 2, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtvjapan.com/vmaj2016/nominees/best-female-video/beyonce|title=Beyonc\u00e9 \u2013 Best Female Video|publisher=[[MTV Japan]]|accessdate=September 2, 2016}}</ref> At the [[2016 Soul Train Music Awards]], Beyonc\u00e9 was nominated for eight awards including Best Female Artist, ''Lemonade'' for Album of the Year, and \"Formation\" for Song and Video of the Year. Beyonc\u00e9 went on to win all four awards. ''Lemonade'' won Best TV Show \u2013 Special or Limited Series at the [[African American Film Critics Association]].<ref name=\":17\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/moonlight-named-best-picture-by-african-american-film-critics-association-955250|title='Moonlight' Named Best Picture by the African American Film Critics Association|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=February 20, 2017}}</ref> At the 2017 [[NAACP Image Awards]], ''Lemonade'' was nominated for [[NAACP Image Award for Outstanding Album|Outstanding Album]] and [[NAACP Image Award for Outstanding Variety \u2013 Series or Special|Outstanding Variety \u2013 Series or Special]], \"Formation\" was nominated for [[NAACP Image Award for Outstanding Song|Outstanding Song]] and [[NAACP Image Award for Outstanding Music Video|Outstanding Music Video]], and \"Freedom\", featuring [[Kendrick Lamar]], was nominated for [[NAACP Image Award for Outstanding Duo or Group|Outstanding Duo, Group or Collaboration]] and [[NAACP Image Award for Outstanding Song|Outstanding Song]]. The album received four awards, including Outstanding Album, Outstanding Song and Outstanding Duo, Group or Collaboration for \"Freedom\" and Outstanding Music Video for \"Formation\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/2017-naacp-image-award-winners-televised-966471|title=2017 NAACP Image Award Winners: Complete List|first1=Hilary|last1=Lewis|first2=Arlene|last2=Washington|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Eldridge Industries]]|date=February 10, 2017|accessdate=March 31, 2017}}</ref> At the 2016 [[ADG Excellence in Production Design Award]]s, ''Lemonade'' received the award for Best Awards or Event Special, as well as \"Hold Up\", \"6 Inch\" and \"Denial\" all being nominated for Best Short Format: Web Series, Music Video or Commercial.<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Hipes|first1=Patrick|title=Art Directors Guild Awards Nominations: 'Rogue One', 'Game Of Thrones' & More|url=http://deadline.com/2017/01/art-directors-guild-nominations-2017-full-list-1201878962/|magazine=Deadline|accessdate=January 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[59th Annual Grammy Awards]], ''Lemonade'' received three nominations: [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]], [[Grammy Award for Best Urban Contemporary Album|Best Urban Contemporary Album]] and [[Grammy Award for Best Music Film|Best Music Film]]. \"[[Formation (song)|Formation]]\" received three as well: [[Grammy Award for Record of the Year|Record of the Year]], [[Grammy Award for Song of the Year|Song of the Year]] and [[Grammy Award for Best Music Video|Best Music Video]]. \"[[Hold Up (Beyonc\u00e9 song)|Hold Up]]\" was nominated for [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Solo Performance|Best Pop Solo Performance]], \"[[Don't Hurt Yourself (Beyonc\u00e9 song)|Don't Hurt Yourself]]\" for [[Grammy Award for Best Rock Performance|Best Rock Performance]] and \"[[Freedom (Beyonc\u00e9 song)|Freedom]]\" for [[Grammy Award for Best Rap/Sung Performance|Best Rap/Sung Performance]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.grammy.com/news/beyonc-leads-59th-grammy-nominations-with-nine|title=Beyonc\u00e9 leads 59th GRAMMY nominations with nine|date=December 6, 2016|publisher=National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref> The album went on to win two awards, Best Urban Contemporary Album and Best Music Video for \"Formation\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.grammy.com/artist/beyonce|title=Beyonc\u00e9|date=March 22, 2013|publisher=National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref> ''Lemonade'' won [[Black Reel Award for Outstanding Television Documentary or Special|Outstanding Television Documentary or Special]] at the [[Black Reel Awards of 2017|2017 Black Reel Awards]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://blackreelawards.com/moonlight-shines-bright/|title=\"Moonlight\" Shines Bright!|date=February 17, 2017|work=Black Reel Awards|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref>\n''Lemonade'' won a [[Peabody Award]] in Entertainment, along with the following description by the board of jurors: \"''Lemonade'' draws from the prolific literary, musical, cinematic, and aesthetic sensibilities of black cultural producers to create a rich tapestry of poetic innovation. The audacity of its reach and fierceness of its vision challenges our cultural imagination, while crafting a stunning and sublime masterpiece about the lives of women of color and the bonds of friendship seldom seen or heard in American popular culture.\"<ref>Blanchard, Margaret,\n [http://www.peabodyawards.com/stories/story/entertainment-winners-named-for-peabody-30 \"Entertainment winners named for Peabody 30\"], Peabody, April 20, 2017.</ref>\n\n== Commercial performance ==\nIn the United States, ''Lemonade'' debuted at number one on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], with 653,000 [[album-equivalent unit]]s, out of which 485,000 were [[pure album sales]]. This made the highest opening-week sales for a female act of the year. Subsequently, she broke the record she previously tied with [[DMX (rapper)|DMX]], by becoming the first artist in the chart's history to have their first six studio albums debut at number one.<ref name=\"debut\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7350372/beyonce-earns-sixth-no-1-album-on-billboard-200-chart-with-lemonade|title=Beyonc\u00e9 Earns Sixth No. 1 Album on Billboard 200 Chart With 'Lemonade'|work=Billboard|date=May 1, 2016|accessdate=May 1, 2016}}</ref> In the same week, Beyonc\u00e9 became the first female artist to chart twelve or more songs on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] at the same time, with every song on the album debuting on the chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7350443/beyonce-lemonade-tracks-debut-hot-100|title=All 12 of Beyonc\u00e9's 'Lemonade' Tracks Debut on Hot 100|work=Billboard|date=May 2, 2016|accessdate=May 2, 2016}}</ref> Additionally, ''Lemonade'' was streamed 115 million times via Tidal, setting a record for the most-streamed album in a single week by a female artist.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/05/03/arts/music/beyonce-lemonade-chart-sales.html|title=Beyonc\u00e9's 'Lemonade' Debuts at No. 1 With Huge Streaming Numbers|work=The New York Times|first=Joe|last=Coscarelli|date=May 3, 2016|accessdate=May 16, 2016}}</ref> The album slipped from number one to number two in its second week, selling 321,000 album-equivalent units, out of which 196,000 were pure album sales. It remained at number two in its third week selling 201,000 album-equivalent units, out of which 153,000 were pure album sales. ''Lemonade'' was certified [[RIAA certification|platinum]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA) in June 2016. According to [[Nielsen Broadcast Data Systems|Nielsen]]'s 2016 year-end report, it had sold 1,554,000 copies and 2,187,000 [[album-equivalent unit]]s in the United States.<ref name=\"salesus\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7647018/drake-views-nielsen-music-top-album-2016-us|title=Drake's 'Views' Is Nielsen Music's Top Album of 2016 in the U.S.|date=January 5, 2017|work=Billboard|accessdate=August 29, 2019}}</ref> Following its April 23, 2019 release on all streaming services, ''Lemonade'' returned to the top ten on the ''Billboard'' 200 at number nine,<ref>https://www.billboard.com/music/beyonce/chart-history/catalog-albums</ref> while its only added song, the original demo of \"Sorry\", debuted at number four on the [[Hot R&B Songs]].<ref>https://www.billboard.com/music/beyonce/chart-history/r-and-b-songs</ref> On May 20, 2019, the album was certified double platinum for shipments of two million copies, and triple platinum on June 13, 2019, for shipments of three million copies. In Canada, the album debuted at number one with sales of 33,000 copies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7358025/drake-views-debuts-at-no-1-on-billboard-200-charts-sets|title=Drake's 'Views' Debuts at No. 1 on Billboard 200 Chart, Sets Streaming Record|work=Billboard|first=Keith|last=Caulfield|date=May 8, 2016|accessdate=May 16, 2016}}</ref> As of April, 2020 is the first year since release that Lemonade has not appeared on the Billboard 200.\n\nThe album debuted at number one on the [[UK Albums Chart]] selling 73,000 copies in its first week of release, with 10,000 equivalent sales (14% of the total sales) accounting for streaming, marking the largest ever for a number-one album since the chart began including streaming.<ref name=\"ukdeb\">{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/beyonc\u00e9s-lemonade-fizzes-to-official-albums-chart-number-1__14763/|title=Beyonc\u00e9's 'Lemonade' fizzes to Official Albums Chart Number 1|last=White|first=Justin|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|date=April 29, 2016|accessdate=May 2, 2016}}</ref> The album marked the singer's third number-one album on the chart and was certified platinum by the [[British Phonographic Industry]] (BPI) on September 9, 2016 for shipments of 300,000 copies.<ref name=\"ukdeb\" /> All of the album's tracks also debuted within the top hundred of the [[UK Singles Chart]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/charts/singles-chart/20160429/7501/|title=Official Singles Chart Top 100 \u2013 29 April 2016 \u2013 05 May 2016|publisher=Official Charts Company|accessdate=May 16, 2016}}</ref> As in the US, 2020 is the first year since release that the album has not appeared on the UK Chart.\n\nIn Australia, ''Lemonade'' sold 20,490 digital copies in its first week, debuting atop the [[ARIA Charts|Australian Albums Chart]] and becoming Beyonc\u00e9's second consecutive number-one album in the country.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/music/beyonces-lemonade-beats-prince-on-australian-music-charts/news-story/d15a541e1fff2c74497699417cb1e907|title=Beyonc\u00e9's 'Lemonade' beats Prince on Australian music charts|work=[[News.com.au]]|date=May 1, 2016|accessdate=May 2, 2016}}</ref> It received a platinum certification from the [[Australian Recording Industry Association]] (ARIA) for shipments of 70,000 copies.<ref name=\"auscert\" />\n\n''Lemonade'' also topped the Irish Albums Chart, where it spent six non-consecutive at number one. [[Billie Eilish]]'s [[When We All Fall Asleep, Where Do We Go?]] is the only album to have achieved this since. ''Lemonade'' spent an additional 4 weeks at number two and, as of 2020, has spent 58 non-consecutive weeks on the chart. As in the US, 2020 is the first year since release that the album has not appeared on the Irish Chart.\n\n''Lemonade'' also peaked atop the charts in Brazil, Croatia, Czech Republic, Flanders, the Netherlands, New Zealand, Norway, Portugal, Scotland, South Korea, and Sweden. By the end of 2016, the album sold 2.5 million copies worldwide according to the [[International Federation of the Phonographic Industry]] (IFPI), being the best-selling album of 2016 worldwide and the third best-selling album of the year in the United States .\n\n== Impact and legacy ==\n[[File:4-44 album cover.png|thumb|left|Beyonc\u00e9's husband [[Jay-Z]]'s thirteenth studio album ''[[4:44]]'' (2017) was noted by critics to be a response to ''Lemonade''.]]\nSeveral musicians were inspired by ''Lemonade''. American rapper [[Snoop Dogg]] named his fourteenth studio album ''[[Coolaid]]'' (2016) after ''Lemonade.''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/68277-snoop-dogg-named-his-coolaid-album-after-beyonces-lemonade/|title=Snoop Dogg Named His Coolaid Album After Beyonc\u00e9's ''Lemonade''|website=Pitchfork|access-date=January 28, 2017}}</ref> British girl group [[Little Mix]] cited ''Lemonade'' as an inspiration for their album ''[[Glory Days (Little Mix album)|Glory Days]]'' (2016).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fuse.tv/videos/2017/01/little-mix-beyonce-interview|title=Little Mix Explain Admiration of Beyonc\u00e9, How 'Lemonade' Inspired Their New Album|last=Interview|website=Fuse|access-date=2019-04-19}}</ref> American singer [[The-Dream]] wrote a response to ''Lemonade'' titled \"Lemon Lean\" in his EP [[Love You to Death (EP)|''Love You To Death'']], saying that the album changed the way people think about their relationships.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/7616416/the-dream-love-you-to-death-ep-interview|title=The-Dream on 'Love You To Death' EP: 'I'm Trying to Find the Rest of the Things That Make Me Whole'|website=Billboard|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/the-dream-talks-love-after-lemonade-why-he-deserves-legendary-status-106465/|title=The-Dream Talks Love After 'Lemonade,' Why He Deserves Legendary Status|last=Leight|first=Elias|last2=Leight|first2=Elias|date=2016-12-15|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref> American singer Lauren Jenkins used ''Lemonade'' as the inspiration for her album and long-form music video ''No Saint''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-country/lauren-jenkins-no-saint-album-beyonce-810591/|title=How Lauren Jenkins Embraced Imperfection (and Beyonce) on Her Debut Album|last=Moss|first=Marissa R.|last2=Moss|first2=Marissa R.|date=2019-03-20|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref> ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' writes that [[Shania Twain]]'s ''[[Now (Shania Twain album)|Now]]'' \"couldn't have existed without\" ''Lemonade'', as an album that \"completely changed the course of breakup album history\" in which the artist is \"someone at their full creative peak pushing herself into new niches, dominating new musical territories.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/country/7989004/shania-twain-now-beyonce-lemonade|title=Shania Twain's 'Now': Not Quite Her 'Lemonade,' But Her First Album in 15 Years Couldn't Have Existed Without It (Critic's Take)|website=Billboard|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref> Sesali Bowen for ''[[Refinery29]]'' suggests that [[Taylor Swift]] was also inspired by ''Lemonade'' for her album [[Reputation (Taylor Swift album)|''Reputation'']], with Swift attempting to emulate Beyonc\u00e9's utilisation of her album as a tool to address personal issues solely through the medium of music.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.refinery29.com/en-gb/2017/11/180783/aylor-swift-reputation-publicity-beyonce-lemonade|title=What Taylor Swift Can Learn From Beyonc\u00e9's Lemonade|last=Bowen|first=Sesali|website=www.refinery29.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> Joe Coscarelli of ''[[The New York Times]]'' describes how \"some brand-name acts are following Beyonc\u00e9\u2019s blueprint with high-concept mini-movies that can add artistic heft to projects,\" with [[Frank Ocean]]'s ''[[Endless (Frank Ocean album)|Endless]]'' and [[Drake (musician)|Drake]]'s ''[[Please Forgive Me (film)|Please Forgive Me]]'' cited as examples of artists' projects inspired by ''Lemonade''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/09/29/arts/music/drake-please-forgive-me-beyonce-videos.html|title=Beyonc\u00e9 Raised the Bar With \u2018Lemonade.\u2019 Now Others Are Leaping, Too.|last=Coscarelli|first=Joe|date=2016-09-28|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-04-19|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> ''Lemonade'' has been said to have set a trend of musicians releasing a TV special together with an album; [[The Lonely Island|Lonely Island]]'s ''[[The Unauthorized Bash Brothers Experience]]'', [[Thom Yorke]]'s ''[[Anima (Thom Yorke album)|Anima]],'' [[Sturgill Simpson]]'s ''[[Sound & Fury (Sturgill Simpson album)|Sound & Fury]]'', and [[Kid Cudi]]'s ''[[Entergalactic]]'' are all cited as examples of projects that have followed the precedent that ''Lemonade'' set.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stereogum.com/2052194/netflix-beyonce-lion-king-homecoming-lemonade/franchises/the-week-in-pop/|title=Some Thoughts On Beyonc\u00e9, Music Trendsetter, And Netflix, Music Trend|date=July 25, 2019|website=Stereogum|access-date=August 6, 2019}}</ref> Kadeen Griffiths from ''[[Bustle (magazine)|Bustle]]'' states that ''Lemonade'', as an album that deals with issues related to black women, \"paved the way\" for [[Alicia Keys]]' ''[[Here (Alicia Keys album)|Here]]'' and [[Solange Knowles|Solange]]'s ''[[A Seat at the Table|A Seat At The Table]].''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bustle.com/p/this-is-what-beyonces-lemonade-meant-to-me-as-a-black-woman-this-is-why-it-needed-to-win-album-of-the-year-37653|title=Why We All Wanted Beyonc\u00e9 To Win At The Grammys|website=Bustle|language=en|access-date=2019-06-18}}</ref> Many critics have noted that [[Jay-Z]]'s thirteenth studio album ''[[4:44 (album)|4:44]]'' (2017) is a response to ''Lemonade'', with Jay-Z referencing lines from ''Lemonade'', such as the \"You better call Becky with the good hair\" line on Beyonc\u00e9's \"[[Sorry (Beyonc\u00e9 song)|Sorry]]\", with Jay-Z retorting: \"Let me alone, Becky\" in \"Family Feud\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://ew.com/music/2017/06/30/jay-z-becky-beyonce-444-lyrics/|title=JAY-Z Swears Off Alleged Mistress 'Becky' for Good: 'Let Me Alone'|date=June 30, 2017|work=EW.com|access-date=July 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[Myf Warhurst]] on [[Double J (radio station)|''Double J'']]'s \"Lunch With Myf\" explains that with ''Lemonade'', Beyonc\u00e9 \"changed [the album] to a narrative with an arc and a story and you have to listen to the entire thing to get the concept... She's brought the album back.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/doublej/music-reads/features/why-beyoncs-lemonade-is-having-such-a-powerful-impact/10269990|title=Why Beyonc\u00e9's Lemonade is having such a powerful impact|date=2016-05-03|website=Double J|language=en-AU|access-date=2019-06-18}}</ref> Legendary musician [[Stevie Wonder]] called ''Lemonade'' \u201ca great work, a great art piece\u201d.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/music-festivals/7386059/stevie-wonder-talks-beyonce-and-why-lemonade-is-a-great-art-bottlerock-2016|title=Stevie Wonder Talks Beyonce and Why 'Lemonade' is 'A Great Art Piece' at BottleRock 2016|website=Billboard|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref> At the [[59th Annual Grammy Awards]] (2017), [[Adele]] dedicated her [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]] award to Beyonc\u00e9 and said: \"The artist of my life is Beyonc\u00e9... the ''Lemonade'' album, is just so monumental.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.etonline.com/awards/grammys/210287_beyonce_cries_after_adele_dedicates_album_of_the_year_grammy_to_lemonade/|title=Beyonc\u00e9 Cries After Emotional Adele Dedicates Her Album of the Year GRAMMY to ''Lemonade''|newspaper=Entertainment Tonight|access-date=February 13, 2017}}</ref> Former [[Director of the Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI director]] [[James Comey]] sang \u201cSandcastles\u201d during an FBI brief.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/james-comey-beyonce-fbi-briefing-sandcastles-trump-lemonade-a-higher-loyalty-book-a8334381.html|title=James Comey sang a Beyonce song during an FBI briefing|date=2018-05-03|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref> For Beyonc\u00e9's 36th birthday, various black female public figures recreated a costume that Beyonc\u00e9 wore in the \"Formation\" music video, including [[Michelle Obama]] and [[Serena Williams]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/michelle-obama-dresses-up-as-beyonce-in-formation-in-birthday-tribute-2017-9|title=Michelle Obama and Serena Williams dressed up as Beyonc\u00e9 to celebrate her birthday|last=UK|first=Rosie Fitzmaurice, Business Insider|website=Business Insider|access-date=2019-06-11}}</ref>\n\nBeyonc\u00e9's use of various genres on ''Lemonade'' has been credited with setting the precedent for music to transcend genre, with ''[[NPR]]'' writing that the album \"leads us to this moment where post-genre becomes a thing\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fuse.tv/2016/04/beyonce-genre-lemonade|title=What Does Beyonc\u00e9's 'Lemonade' Tell Us About Genre?|last=In-Depth|website=Fuse|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/10/07/767903285/the-2010s-5-ways-beyonc-defined-the-decade-in-music|title=The 2010s: 5 Ways Beyonc\u00e9 Defined The Decade In Music|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> The use of various genres has also been credited with kickstarting the reclamation of certain genres by black people. \"[[Daddy Lessons]]\" has been credited as starting a trend of \"pop stars toying with American West and Southern aesthetics,\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/welcome-to-the-yee-yee-club-bitch-805169/|title=Giddy Up! Here\u2019s What You Need to Know About the Yeehaw Agenda|work=Rolling Stone}}</ref> as well as setting the precedent for \"The Yeehaw Agenda,\" the trend of reclaiming black [[cowboy]] culture through music and fashion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.texasmonthly.com/the-culture/yeehaw-agenda-country-movement/|title=How the \u2018Yeehaw Agenda\u2019 Disrupted Texas Country Culture for Good|date=2019-09-06|website=Texas Monthly|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://observer.com/2019/02/this-years-grammys-were-the-ultimate-tribute-to-yeehaw-culture/|title=This Year\u2019s Grammys Were the Ultimate Tribute to Yeehaw Culture|date=2019-02-11|website=Observer|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> \"[[Don't Hurt Yourself (Beyonc\u00e9 song)|Don't Hurt Yourself]]\" has been credited with the reclaiming of rock by black women, with Brittany Spanos for ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' writing that \"the re-imagination of what rock can be and who can sing it by Beyonc\u00e9 and her superstar peers is giving the genre a second life \u2013 and may be what can save it.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/how-beyonces-lemonade-reclaims-rocks-black-female-legacy-67463/|title=How Beyonce's 'Lemonade' Reclaims Rock's Black Female Legacy|last=Spanos|first=Brittany|last2=Spanos|first2=Brittany|date=2016-04-26|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n''Lemonade'' has also inspired artists in media other than music, including art, literature, film and theatre. Fashion stylist Salvador Camarena paid homage to ''Lemonade'' by designing a room dedicated to the album during [[Modernism Week]], saying \u201cThat album is such a visually stunning album. There are so many iconic looks from the video, I kind of wanted to implement that world into that room.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.desertsun.com/story/life/entertainment/events/modernism/2017/02/20/beyonc-inspired-bathroom-featured-modernism-week-show-house/97723022/|title=Visuals from Beyonc\u00e9's 'Lemonade' inspire Modernism Week show house stylist|last=Pena|first=Xochitl|website=Desert Sun|language=en|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref> [[Bill Condon]], director of the film ''[[Beauty and the Beast (2017 film)|Beauty and the Beast]]'' (2017) says the visuals behind ''Lemonade'' inspired him for the movie: \"You look at Beyonc\u00e9's brilliant movie ''Lemonade'', this genre is taking on so many different forms\u2026 I do think that this very old-school break-out-into-song traditional musical is something that people understand again and really want.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://screenrant.com/beauty-and-the-beast-la-la-land-musical/|title=How ''La La Land'' Helped Live-Action ''Beauty and the Beast'' Remake|date=March 18, 2017|work=Screen Rant|access-date=March 27, 2017}}</ref> The [[Young adult fiction|young adult]] [[anthology]] ''A Phoenix First Must Burn'' edited by Patrice Caldwell, which explores \"the Black experience through fantasy, science fiction, and magic\", has the aim of \"evoking Beyonc\u00e9\u2019s Lemonade for a teen audience\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goodreads.com/work/best_book/68284055-a-phoenix-first-must-burn|title=A Phoenix First Must Burn|website=www.goodreads.com|access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref> The character of [[Catherine of Aragon]] in the [[West End theatre|West End]] and [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] musical ''[[Six (musical)|Six]]'' was inspired by \"''Lemonade''-era Beyonc\u00e9\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cheatsheet.com/entertainment/six-the-musical-which-modern-day-pop-stars-are-the-queens-inspired-by.html/|title='Six' Creators Reveal Which Modern-Day Pop Star Influenced Each of Henry VIII's Wives in the Musical|last=Wright|first=Catherine|last2=Articles|first2=More|date=2019-12-23|website=Showbiz Cheat Sheet|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-07|last3=December 23|first3=2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2020/03/six-broadway-musical-henry-viii-queens.html|title=How Six Created Its 16th-Century Pop-Star Queens|last=McHenry|first=Jackson|date=2020-03-04|website=Vulture|language=en-us|access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref> The cover of [[Marvel Comics|Marvel's]] 2017 ''[[Miss America (America Chavez)|America]]'' comic book paid homage to the \"Formation\" music video, with its illustrator saying \"America is a comic that is all about representation, feminism and fighting for what\u2019s right... I could think of no better parallel than Beyonc\u00e9.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://time.com/4649086/marvel-america-beyonce/|title=This Marvel Comic Book Cover Was Inspired by Beyonc\u00e9|website=Time|access-date=2019-04-19}}</ref>\n\nSales for Warsan Shire's [[chapbook]] \"Teaching My Mother How to Give Birth\" increased by 700 to 800% after her poetry was included in the ''Lemonade'' film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/industry-news/publisher-news/article/70377-warsan-shire-s-sales-spike-after-lemonade-shoutout.html|last=Publishers Weekly|title=Warshan Shire's sales spike after 'Lemonade' shoutout|date=17 May 2016|access-date=16 June 2019}}</ref> Beyonc\u00e9's mention of [[Red Lobster]] in \"Formation\" increased sales at the restaurant chain by 33%, which made employees rename popular menu items after Beyonc\u00e9 and call the effect the \"Beyonc\u00e9 Bounce\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2016/02/08/a-beyonce-mention-sends-red-lobster-sales-higher.html|title=A Beyonce mention sends Red Lobster sales higher|last=Whitten|first=Sarah|date=2016-02-08|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2019-06-18}}</ref> Designers of the costumes that Beyonc\u00e9 wore in the ''Lemonade'' film spoke with ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]'' about the impact that this had on their careers; for example, Natalia Fedner, who designed Beyonc\u00e9's dress for \"Hold Up\", stated that because of the dress's inclusion in Lemonade, \"I was on '[[Entertainment Tonight]]' being hailed as a 'designer to watch'.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/style/2016/05/beyonce-lemonade-designers|title=Six 'Lemonade' Designers Talk About the Impact of Beyonc\u00e9's Project|website=Complex|language=en|access-date=2019-06-18}}</ref> The inclusion of imagery from the 1991 film ''[[Daughters of the Dust]]'' in the visuals for ''Lemonade'' helped bring the film back to theatres, with director [[Julie Dash]] stating that ''Lemonade'' \"just took me places that I had not been seeing in a long, long time. It just re-confirmed a lot of things that I know to be true about visual style and visual metaphors. And the use of visual metaphors in creating, redefining, and re-framing a Creole culture within this new world.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2016/08/daughters-of-the-dust-exclusive|title=How Beyonc\u00e9\u2019s Lemonade Helped Bring a Groundbreaking Film Back to Theaters|last=Nast|first=Cond\u00e9|website=Vanity Fair|access-date=2019-04-19}}</ref> The use of the lemon and bee [[emoji]]s increased due to the release of Lemonade, with a [[Twitter]] spokesperson telling ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]:'' \"Before ''Lemonade'', the lemon emoji had no meaning. Since the launch of ''Lemonade'', the emoji has taken on a meaning of its own\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/4631309/beyonce-lemonade-impact/|title=See the Far-reaching Impact of Beyonc\u00e9's Lemonade|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2019-06-18}}</ref> The [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Long Form Video|MTV Video Music Award for Breakthrough Long Form Video]], which Beyonc\u00e9 ultimately won at the [[2016 MTV Video Music Awards]], was reintroduced after 25 years due to the ''Lemonade'' film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thisisinsider.com/mtv-breakthrough-long-form-video-vma-award-beyonce-2016-8|title=MTV brought back a VMA award that hasn't been given out in 25 years for Beyonc\u00e9|last=Grebey|first=James|website=INSIDER|access-date=2019-04-19}}</ref>\n\n[[University of Texas at San Antonio]] offered a class in the Fall of 2016 based on the album. The course, titled \"Black Women, Beyonc\u00e9 and Popular Culture\", explored how the visual album \"is a meditation on contemporary black womanhood,\" before advancing and diving into the \"theoretical, historical, and literary frameworks of black feminism,\" according to the syllabus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2016/09/utsa-black-women-beyonce-popular-culture-course-lemonade|title=UTSA to Offer \"Black Women, Beyonc\u00e9 & Popular Culture\" Course on ''Lemonade''|website=Complex|access-date=February 17, 2017}}</ref> The [[University of Tennessee at Chattanooga]] hosted a \"Lemonade Week\" in April 2017, which featured discussions on feminism, theatrical performances, celebrations of African-American women writers and poets, and choreography tutorials.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesfreepress.com/news/chattanooganow/outabout/story/2017/mar/30/beyonces-music-inspires-utcs-lemonade-week/420047/|title=Beyonce's music inspires UTC's Lemonade Week|date=2017-03-30|website=timesfreepress.com|access-date=2019-04-19}}</ref> [[Harvard University]] hosted \"The Lemon Drop\": a discussion that explored the nuances of ''Lemonade.''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hutchinscenter.fas.harvard.edu/event/kinitra-d-brooks-and-kameelah-l-martin-present-lemonade-reader-beyonc%C3%A9-black-feminism|title=Kinitra D. Brooks and Kameelah L. Martin present 'The Lemonade Reader: Beyonc\u00e9, Black Feminism and Spirituality'|website=hutchinscenter.fas.harvard.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref> [[University of Arkansas]] offered a course that analysed the influence of black feminism on Beyonc\u00e9 and ''Lemonade.''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tips.uark.edu/faculty-spotlight-beyonce-and-black-feminism-designing-and-developing-your-dream-course/|title=Faculty Spotlight: \u201cBeyonc\u00e9 and Black Feminism\u201d \u2013 Designing and Developing Your Dream Course {{!}} Teaching Innovation and Pedagogical Support|website=tips.uark.edu|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref> University of Pennsylvania ran two courses that explored politics, race and gender through the study of ''Lemonade''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.english.upenn.edu/courses/undergraduate/2018/spring/engl084.401|title=Department of English|website=www.english.upenn.edu|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.english.upenn.edu/courses/undergraduate/2017/spring/engl200.306|title=Department of English|website=www.english.upenn.edu|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> [[Michigan State University]] hosted a discussion on ''Lemonade'' as part of their series for \"exchanging ideas and exploring the lived experiences of underrepresented and marginalized communities\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bookings.lib.msu.edu/event/6291605|title=Encompass Series: A Discussion of Beyonce's Lemonade|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> [[Chatham University]] based a writing class on ''Lemonade'', where \"students get to examine how they fit into the power systems around them\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.theincline.com/2017/09/11/hold-up-theres-a-chatham-university-class-all-about-beyonces-lemonade/|title=Hold up: There's a Chatham University class all about Beyonc\u00e9's 'Lemonade'|website=The Incline|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref> [[Valdosta State University]] offered a course on ''Lemonade'', \"unpacking the many themes found in \u201cLemonade,\u201d including black identity, feminism, marital infidelity, sisterhood, and faith.\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.valdosta.edu/about/news/releases/2019/02/vsu-explores-the-black-female-experience-through-beyonc%C3%A9s-lemonade.php|title=VSU Explores the Black Female Experience Through Beyonc\u00e9\u2019s \u201cLemonade\u201d - Valdosta State University|website=www.valdosta.edu|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref> The [[College of Charleston]] hosted a discussion by black feminist scholars, exploring \"Beyonc\u00e9's use of southern landscape, black women, music, and African-based spirituality\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/events/ehhp-alumni-center-86-wentworth-street-charleston-sc-29424/the-lemonade-reader-black-feminist-scholars-discuss-beyonc%C3%A9/598079680722515/|title=The Lemonade Reader--Black Feminist Scholars discuss Beyonc\u00e9|website=www.facebook.com|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref> [[University of North Georgia]] offered a class entitled \"Okay, Ladies, Now Let\u2019s Get in Formation: Intersectional Feminism in Beyonc\u00e9\u2019s Lemonade\" that explored the music, lyrics and visuals of ''Lemonade''.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Parker|first=Rachel|date=2018-03-23|title=Okay, Ladies, Now Let\u2019s Get in Formation: Intersectional Feminism in Beyonc\u00e9\u2019s Lemonade|url=https://digitalcommons.northgeorgia.edu/ngresearchconf/2018/English_Communications/18|journal=University of North Georgia Annual Research Conference}}</ref> In partnership with the [[Zora Neale Hurston Festival of the Arts and Humanities]], a talk at [[Seminole State College of Florida|Seminole State College]] \"discussed how Beyonc\u00e9 embodies the conjure woman in her iconic audiovisual work ''Lemonade'' as a contemporary revision of [[Zora Neale Hurston]]\u2019s groundbreaking study of conjure and its place in black women\u2019s spirit work.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.seminolestate.edu/newsroom/article/6114/author-dr-kinitra-brooks-discusses-how-beyonce-embodies-the-conjure-woman|title=Author Dr. Kinitra Brooks discusses how Beyonc\u00e9 embodies the conjure woman|website=Seminole State College|language=en|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref> Kinitra Brooks and Kameelah Martin have produced \"The Lemonade Reader\", described as \"an educational tool to support and guide discussions of the visual album at postgraduate and undergraduate levels, [which] critiques ''Lemonade''\u2019s multiple Afrodiasporic influences, visual aesthetics, narrative arc of grief and healing, and ethnomusicological reach.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crcpress.com/The-Lemonade-Reader/Brooks-Martin/p/book/9781138596788|title=The Lemonade Reader|website=CRC Press|language=en|access-date=2019-06-18}}</ref> [[University of Texas at Austin]] professor Omise\u2019eke Tinsley wrote a book entitled \"Beyonc\u00e9 in Formation: Remixing Black Feminism\", which \"analyzes Beyonc\u00e9\u2019s visual album, ''Lemonade'', in relation to the sexuality and gender of black women\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailytexanonline.com/2018/10/30/ut-professor-celebrates-new-book-discussing-beyonc\u00e9-and-black-feminism|title=UT Professor celebrates new book discussing Beyonc\u00e9 and black feminism - The Daily Texan|website=www.dailytexanonline.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref> [[University at Albany, SUNY|University of Albany]] professor Janell Hobson produced a lesson plan based on her class on ''Lemonade'', saying \"Beyonc\u00e9\u2019s ''Lemonade'' stimulates class discussions and assignments as a highly visible pop project striving to create deeper conversations on the meanings of blackness, womanhood, and feminism.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ffc.twu.edu/issue_8-1/lesson_Hobson_8-1.html|title=Films for the Feminist Classroom - Issue 8.1|website=ffc.twu.edu|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref>\n\n''Lemonade'' was parodied and was paid homage to in various media. In an episode of ''[[Unbreakable Kimmy Schmidt]]'' titled \"Kimmy's Roommate Lemonades!\", character [[Titus Andromedon]] parodied the videos for \"Hold Up\", \"Sorry\" and \"All Night\" after he suspects his boyfriend of infidelity, coining the term \"Lemonading\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bustle.com/p/lemonade-vs-the-unbreakable-kimmy-schmidt-homage-shows-how-much-beyonces-album-impacted-pop-culture-58372|title=Titus Makes 'Lemonade' Out Of His Heartbreak On 'Kimmy Schmidt'|website=Bustle|language=en|access-date=2019-06-11}}</ref> The \"Hold Up\" music video was also paid homage to in ''[[The Simpsons]],''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/tv/beyonce-public-enemys-flavor-fav-make-cameos-simpsons-hip-hop-special-1946806|title=Beyonc\u00e9 and Public Enemy's Flavor Fav make cameos in The Simpsons hip-hop special|last=Jones|first=Damian|date=2017-01-16|website=NME|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-11}}</ref> ''[[The Ellen DeGeneres Show]],''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/ellen-degeneres-wants-make-you-893687|title=Ellen DeGeneres Wants to Make Sure You Saw Her Part in Beyonce's 'Lemonade'|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2019-06-11}}</ref> ''[[The Late Show with Stephen Colbert]],''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2016/04/late-night-hosts-beyonce-lemonade|title=Watch the Men of Late Night Grapple With Beyonc\u00e9\u2019s Lemonade|last=Bradley|first=Laura|website=Vanity Fair|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> and ''[[The Daily Show]].''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/beyonce-lemonade-james-corden-stephen-887653|title=Late Night Hosts Mock Beyonce's 'Lemonade'|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> ''[[Saturday Night Live|SNL]]'' produced two sketches on ''Lemonade'': one entitled \"The Day Beyonc\u00e9 Turned Black\" after Beyonc\u00e9 released the \"unapologetically black\" \"Formation\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/showtracker/la-et-st-beyonce-turned-black-snl-skit-20160214-story.html|title='The Day Beyonc\u00e9 Turned Black' is the best 'SNL' skit ever|last=Anderson|first=Tre'vell|website=latimes.com|access-date=2019-06-11}}</ref> and the other entitled \"Melanianade\" which parodied the \"Sorry\" music video featuring impersonations of [[Donald Trump]]'s female family members and aides.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2016/10/melanianade-snl-gives-trump-women-a-beyonce-themed-revenge-anthem.html|title=Melanianade: SNL Gives Trump Women a Beyonc\u00e9-Themed Revenge Anthem|last=Politi|first=Daniel|date=2016-10-16|website=Slate Magazine|language=en|access-date=2019-06-11}}</ref> In a ''[[Late Night with Seth Meyers]]'' sketch titled \"Beyonc\u00e9 Lemonade Late Night Aftermath\", females staffers empowered by ''Lemonade'' paid homage to the visuals, costumes, songs and poetry featured in the film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7350228/seth-meyers-beyonce-lemonade-late-night-aftermath-iggy-azalea-teen-slang|title=Seth Meyers Shares The 'Beyonce Lemonade Late Night Aftermath,' Teaches Iggy Azalea Teen Slang|website=Billboard|access-date=2019-06-11}}</ref> ''[[The Late Late Show with James Corden]]'' produced a parody entitled \"Lemonjames: A Visual Monologue\", where [[James Corden]] gave his monologue by recreating parts of the ''Lemonade'' film such as the \"Pray You Catch Me\", \"Don't Hurt Yourself\" and \"6 Inch\" music videos.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://acclaimmag.com/music/watch-james-corden-spoofs-beyonces-lemonade-video/|title=Watch: James Corden spoofs Beyonc\u00e9's 'Lemonade' video|date=2016-04-28|website=Acclaim Magazine|language=en-us|access-date=2019-06-11}}</ref> Actress [[Goldie Hawn]] and comedian [[Amy Schumer]] produced a parody of \"Formation\". The Season 2 premiere of [[Crazy Ex-Girlfriend]] featured a musical number that was an homage to ''Lemonade'', including parodies of \"Formation\" and \"Pray You Catch Me\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/entertainthis/2016/10/21/crazy-ex-girlfriend-lemonade-beyonce/92392792/|title=Behind 'Crazy Ex-Girlfriend's 'Lemonade'-inspired premiere|last=Mallenbaum|first=Carly|website=USA TODAY|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n[[Museum of Design Atlanta]] (MODA) announced \"The ''Lemonade'' Project\", a twelve-month series of conversations centered around the visual album. The series will explore the themes of race, gender and class addressed by the album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.museumofdesign.org/lemonade/|title=The ''Lemonade'' Project|website=MODA|access-date=February 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2020 ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]'' article titled \"The [[African-American art|African-American Art]] Shaping the 21st Century\", which contained 35 prominent black artists talking about the work that inspires them most, American actress [[Kerry Washington]] relayed about ''Lemonade'':<blockquote>I think ''Lemonade'' really was so culture-shifting in terms of [[Gender role|gender roles]], in terms of [[fidelity]], in terms of how we think about [[marriage]] today, how we think about [[Hip hop|hip-hop]] today, how we think about [[feminism]], how we think about [[Power (social and political)|power]]. [[Visual arts|Visually]], [[Music|musically]], but also [[Political sociology|sociopolitically]], [[Anthropology|anthropologically]], ''Lemonade'' is a game changer. It\u2019s just so big.\n\n\u2014\u200a[[Kerry Washington]], \"The African-American Art Shaping the 21st Century\", ''[[The New York Times]]'' <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2020/03/19/arts/african-american-art-inspiration.html|title=35 Top African-American Artists on the Work That Inspires Them|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-19|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref></blockquote>The release of \"Formation\" and the consequent performance at the [[Super Bowl 50 halftime show]] caused both conversation and controversy due to its \"unapologetic blackness\". Many articles and think pieces were produced discussing the importance and meaning of the song and performance, such as the [[BBC]], who produced an article entitled \"Beyonc\u00e9's Super Bowl performance: Why was it so significant?\",<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-35520636|title=Why was Beyonce's Super Bowl show significant?|date=2016-02-08|access-date=2019-06-18|language=en-GB}}</ref> and ''[[TheWrap]]'', who produced an article entitled \"Why Beyonc\u00e9's Formation\u2019 Matters So Much: A Perfectly Choreographed Political Debut Before 112 Million.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/why-beyonce-formation-matters-so-much-a-perfectly-choreographed-political-debut-before-112-million/|title=Why Beyonce's 'Formation' Matters So Much|date=2016-02-11|website=TheWrap|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-18}}</ref> A rally held against Beyonc\u00e9 and her Super Bowl performance was called \"the worst-attended protest ever\" by the ''[[New York Post]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2016/02/16/anti-beyonce-rally-is-the-worst-attended-protest-ever/|title=Anti-Beyonce rally is the worst-attended protest ever|last=O'Neill|first=Natalie|date=2016-02-16|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=2019-06-18}}</ref> ''Lemonade'' as a whole also inspired many think pieces, particularly written by black women, that analyze the messages and significance of the album,<ref name=\"essence.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.essence.com/celebrity/beyonce-lemonade-black-women-thought-provoking-think-pieces/|title=Beyonce and Lemonade Inspire Think Pieces|website=Essence|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/how-beyonces-lemonade-exposes-inner-lives-of-black-women-36868/|title=How Beyonce's 'Lemonade' Exposes Inner Lives of Black Women|last=Robinson|first=Zandria F.|last2=Robinson|first2=Zandria F.|date=2016-04-28|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/hannahgiorgis/i-aint-sorry|title=All The Best Pieces About Beyonc\u00e9's Lemonade|website=BuzzFeed News|language=en|access-date=2019-06-18}}</ref> such as Miriam Bale for ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' who named ''Lemonade'' \"a revolutionary work of [[black feminism]]\".<ref name=\"essence.com\" /> \n\nMegan Carpentier of ''[[The Guardian]]'' named the album \"a pop culture phenomenon\" and wrote: \"It is not an exaggeration to say that there is no other living musical artist who could ignite such a broad and unavoidable conversation just by releasing a new album \u2013 even a visual one.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/apr/26/beyonce-lemonade-jay-z-becky-pop-culture|title=How Beyonc\u00e9's Lemonade became a pop culture phenomenon|last=Carpentier|first=Megan|date=April 26, 2016|newspaper=The Guardian|issn=0261-3077|access-date=January 28, 2017}}</ref> Writing in the same publication, Syreeta McFadden notes that the \"[[Formation (song)|Formation]]\" video depicts archetypal southern black women \"in ways that we haven't seen frequently represented in popular art or culture\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/feb/08/beyonce-formation-black-american-narrative-the-margins|title=Beyonc\u00e9's Formation reclaims black America's narrative from the margins|date=February 8, 2016|newspaper=The Guardian|issn=0261-3077|access-date=January 28, 2017}}</ref> Melissa Harris-Perry of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine said that \"Beyonc\u00e9 publicly embraced explicitly feminist blackness at a politically risky moment.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://time.com/time-person-of-the-year-2016-beyonce-runner-up/|title=TIME Person of the Year Runner Up: Beyonc\u00e9|website=Time|access-date=January 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\nCredits adapted from the album's [[liner notes]]<ref name=\"Album booklet\">{{cite AV media notes|others = Beyonc\u00e9 |title = Lemonade |year = 2016 |type = booklet |publisher = [[Parkwood Entertainment|Parkwood]]}}</ref>\n{{Track listing\n| headline = ''Lemonade'' {{nobold|\u2013 Disc one (Audio)}}\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n| title_width = 30%\n| writing_width = 40%\n| extra_width = 30%\n| total_length = 45:42\n\n| title1 = [[Pray You Catch Me]]\n| length1 = 3:15\n| writer1 = {{hlist|[[Beyonc\u00e9]]|[[Kevin Garrett (musician)|Kevin Garrett]]|[[James Blake (musician)|James Blake]]}}\n| extra1 = {{hlist|Beyonc\u00e9{{ref|a|[a]}}|Garrett}}\n\n| title2 = [[Hold Up (song)|Hold Up]]\n| writer2 = {{flatlist|\n* Beyonc\u00e9\n* [[Diplo|Thomas Wesley Pentz]]\n* [[Ezra Koenig]]\n* [[Emile Haynie]]\n* [[Joshua Tillman]]\n* [[MNEK|Uzoechi Emenike]]\n* [[MeLo-X|Sean Rhoden]]\n* [[Doc Pomus]]\n* [[Mort Shuman|Mort Schuman]]{{ref|e|[e]}}\n* [[Soulja Boy|DeAndre Way]]\n* Antonio Randolph\n* Kelvin McConnell\n* [[Brian Chase]]\n* [[Karen Orzolek]]\n* [[Nick Zinner]]}}\n| extra2 = {{hlist|Beyonc\u00e9{{ref|a|[a]}}|[[Diplo]]|Koenig}}\n| length2 = 3:41\n\